<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Provide New Food Aid to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Canada announced today that it
will provide 4.5 million Canadian dollars (3.2 million US dollars)
in additional food aid to famine victims in the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
The Canadian International Development Agency (CIDA) will
provide food to the DPRK in the form of up to 2.5 million dollars
(1.8 million US dollars) worth of canned fish, by way of the World
Food Program (WFP).
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Canadian Food Grains Bank will provide up to 2
million dollars (1.4 million US dollars) worth of Canadian grains.
</P>
<P>
"North Korea is experiencing a famine unprecedented in its
history," said Diane Marleau, Canadian minister for international
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We want to do our part to ensure that North Koreans,
especially the children most severely affected, have enough to
eat," she added.
</P>
<P>
Canada decided to provide additional food aid to the DPRK after
a recent WFP appeal, which said the Asian country needs at least
330,000 metric tons of food aid to double rations for children six
years old and under.
</P>
<P>
With the new contribution, Canadian aid to the DPRK to
alleviate the effects of famine now totals over 10 million dollars
(7.2 million US dollars), according to CIDA figures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
