<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Plans Tougher Punishment of Neo-Nazi Youths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The German government is planning
legislation for tougher punishment of violent neo-Nazi youths in
the country, according to a senior member of Chancellor Helmut
Kohl's party today.
</P>
<P>
Bonn is also considering providing police with better means to
listen in on cell-phones being used by extremist suspects, said
Erwin Marschewski, the domestic policy spokesman for Kohl's
Christian Democratic alliance parliamentary faction.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Neue Osnabruecker Zeitung newspaper,
Marschewski said the number of neo-Nazis ready to use violence has
risen to 9,000 in Germany. "The bad thing is that these extremists
are increasingly arming themselves," he added.
</P>
<P>
Illegal weapons were being imported from ex-Yugoslavia, he
said.
</P>
<P>
A government report issued earlier this year reported the
figure of violent neo-Nazis at 6,400. It also showed that reported
rightist crimes in Germany totaled 8,730 in 1996, compared with
7,896 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, male youths committed majority of the
violent rightist crimes in Germany. Of the 751 people convicted of
such attacks last year, it said, over 66 percent were aged between
16 and 20 and only 4 percent were female.
</P>
<P>
Notably, there have been repeated, unprovoked attacks by
neo-Nazi youths in eastern Germany in recent years, showed press
reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
