<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Tax Relations With Inland Area Elaborated (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Officials from the Ministry of
Finance and State Administration of Taxation said here today that
tax laws and regulations of the inland area will not apply to the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, they said that according the
Basic Law of the HKSAR, Hong Kong is a special administrative
region of the People's Republic of China and, in line with the
"one country, two systems" principle, will continue its previous
political and economic systems.
</P>
<P>
According to the officials, Hong Kong will enact laws on its
own for taxes, tax rates, tax reductions, allowances, and
exemptions and other matters of taxation.
</P>
<P>
In reply to issues on Hong Kong's agreements with foreign
countries on taxes, the officials quoted the Basic Law's Article
153 as saying, "the application to the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region of international agreements to which the
People's Republic of China is or becomes a party shall be decided
by the Central People's Government, in accordance with the
circumstances and needs of the region, and after consulting the
government of the region."
</P>
<P>
They said that the current 56 tax agreements signed by the
Chinese government with foreign countries only apply in the inland
area, because they were drafted according to the characteristics
of the inland area and those of the foreign countries involved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Tax Relations With Inland Area Elaborated (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The officials noted that Article 151 of the Basic Law clearly
states that "the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region may on
its own, using the name 'Hong Kong, China' maintain or develop
relations and conclude and implement agreements with foreign
states and regions and relevant international organizations in
appropriate areas, including the economy, trade, finance and
money, shipping, communications, tourism, culture, and sports."
</P>
<P>
After July 1, they said, the central government will continue
to welcome Hong Kong investors. Those who pay taxes in accordance
with the law will continue to enjoy preferential tax policies
given to overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
The officials noted that Hong Kong investors and those who get
income from the inland area will continue to follow the current
tax policies of the inland area for foreign companies,
enterprises, economic organizations and individuals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Tax Relations With Inland Area Elaborated (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On the difference between Hong Kong investors and those from
other regions, the officials said, the preferential policies
signed between China and the rest of the world are in fact not the
same as tax reductions or exemptions.
</P>
<P>
The basic idea of avoiding double taxation is to co-ordinate
or divide jurisdiction over taxes between the two countries
involved, which is a means of avoiding double taxation.
</P>
<P>
If many countries collect taxes from their citizens' domestic
and foreign incomes, both sides reserve the jurisdiction over
their own citizens while admitting the prior tax of the other
country, where their citizen's income is earned.
</P>
<P>
Taxpayers should note the double taxation jurisdictions, and
preferential treatment in one country does not indicate the
person's final taxes because the home country can still have tax
jurisdiction while the country of income can reduce or exempt
taxes, they explained.
</P>
<P>
In actual circumstances, the amount of taxes Hong Kong
investors pay is not higher than those of other overseas
investors in the inland area. Overseas investors in inland areas
are taxed by both the Chinese inland area and their home country,
while Hong Kong business people need only pay taxes to the inland
department because Hong Kong has regional jurisdiction principles.
</P>
<P>
The actual taxes of overseas investors are usually decided by
their home countries' tax policies, while Hong Kong investors'
taxes are only decided by the inland area.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Hong Kong investors and other overseas investors'
tax status should be compared according to both their taxes in the
inland area and the home country or area of residence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Tax Relations With Inland Area Elaborated (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Trade between the inland area and the HKSAR, they said, is
regarded as between two different tariff zones of one sovereign
country after the return of Hong Kong to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
In taxation, the inland area regards Hong Kong as it does in
trade with foreign companies, enterprises, and other economic
organizations and individuals, and this will continue, they said.
</P>
<P>
Import tariffs, value-added tax, and consumption tax are to be
paid on goods imported from Hong Kong to the inland area, while
goods exported to Hong Kong can be exempt from taxes or get refund
according to appropriate regulations.
</P>
<P>
The officials also talked about some basic principles in
dealing with the issue of double taxation in the inland area and
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
First, an agreement to avoid double taxation that is usually
signed between two sovereign countries should not be used between
the Chinese inland area and Hong Kong because the problem should
be restricted to areas within one sovereign country but under
different systems, they noted.
</P>
<P>
Second, according to Hong Kong tax laws, Hong Kong residents do
not need to pay income tax on income earned outside the region and
there is similar articles in the inland tax laws. This basically
avoids the possibility of double taxation, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
But, double taxation may not be ruled out in certain cases,
because of differences in standards and in certain laws in the two
areas, they pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Individuals or units can appeal to the central government's
finance departments to settle the issue with their counterparts
in the HKSAR through consultations, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
