<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ross Continues Mediation Amid Positive Signs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Amid some positive signs,
United States peace envoy Dennis Ross continued intensive shuttle
diplomacy today aimed at restoring the stalled
Israeli-Palestinian security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Ross held a flurry of talks with Israeli officials, Egyptian
Ambassador Mohammed Bassiouny and European Union (EU) peace envoy
Miguel Moratinos in a bid to mobilize all the peace efforts to
break the ice in Israeli-Palestinian relations.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy met separately with Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy and Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai today after
succeeding in arranging a meeting between Israeli officials and
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat and
Palestinian security officials overnight in Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Ross met separately with Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Arafat each twice. After 11 p.m. in the
night, Ross headed back to Ramallah to hold the second meeting
with Arafat, accompanied by Netanyahu's attorney Yitzhak Molcho
and head of the General Security Service, Ami Ayalon.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Israeli and Palestinian security officials
was the first since the double bombings in Jerusalem's Mahane
Yehuda market on July 30, in which 15 people were killed and 170
others wounded.
</P>
<P>
But Ross donwplayed the importance of the meeting after his
talks with Levy, and stressed that he hoped for substantial
results.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting that took place last night and (those) will be
taking place are steps in the direction of reestablishing their
relationship. Clearly, what's important is not meetings for their
own sake, but meetings will produce tangible results," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ross revealed that he did not expect to remain much longer in
the region, indicating that both Israelis and Palestinians should
show flexibility to achieve quick results in restoring the
security cooperation. This would pave the way for a much-expected
visit to the region by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side was apparently disappointed with Ross'
stress solely on Israel's security needs, and wanted the U.S. to
be more balanced by addressing the Palestinian complaints about
Israel's punitive sanctions taken following the Jerusalem
bombings, including the closure, and halt of transferring tax
revenues.
</P>
<P>
In a rare gesture, Egyptian Ambassador Mohammed Bassiouny
expressed support to Ross' efforts to restore the
Israeli-Palestinian security ties. "Now we are talking only about
security coordination and (how) to set up the atmosphere, and
after that Mrs. Albright will come to continue the American
efforts," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Ross also met today with EU envoy Moratinos to brief him on his
meetings with Israeli and Palestinian leaders. Moratinos, who met
with Arafat early in the day, disclosed that EU was sending an
anti-terrorism expert to help the PNA fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel continued exerting pressure on the PNA to
launch a fight against terrorism. Uzi Arad, Netanyahu's adviser
on diplomatic affairs, told the American television network CNN
that the current situation remained "serious", and the PNA must
fulfil its commitments to fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Asked what the consequence would be if the PNA refuses to
accept the Israeli demand, Arad warned: "Otherwise we will have no
progress, it's as simple as that." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
