<HEADLINE> BBC Offers Live Coverage of India/Pakistan 50th </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- BBC News is planning one of its
largest ever live broadcasting operation to cover celebrations
marking the 50th anniversary of the independence of India and
Pakistan, according to a BBC announcement here today.
</P>
<P>
In Delhi, BBC has constructed a temporary studio at its
headquarters in Rafi Marg, near the parliament. Presenters Nik
Gowing for BBC World TV and Max Perrson for BBC World Service
Radio will be coming out from London to anchor coverage in India.
</P>
<P>
In Islamabad, Nisha Pillai will anchor live coverage of
Pakistan's Independence Day for BBC World and Peter Biles will be
reporting for BBC World Service.
</P>
<P>
BBC has been reporting on this part of the world for more than
50 years, and this event is obviously very special to the
corporation.
</P>
<P>
This was recognized when the Indian government granted BBC
special limited permission to broadcast its programs live via
satellite to India and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
BBC World and BBC World Service will be covering key events of
the 50th anniversary celebrations live, such as the midnight
parliamentary session and Prime Minister I.K. Gujral's speech from
the Red Fort.
</P>
<P>
There are also plans to travel to the Wagah/Atari border
crossing to cover a candlelight vigil by peace activists from both
countries on the night of August 14 and 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
