<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Win Five Gold Medals at Pan Pacific Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Swimmers from the United States
took five of the eight gold medals awarded Monday in the Pan
Pacific championships in Fukuoka, Japan, while Australia grabbed
the other three.
</P>
<P>
All of the winning times were the fastest in the world this
year, including the quickest by a U.S. team in the 4x200 meters
freestyle relay since 1988 and the sixth fastest time ever in the
men's 100 breaststroke, reports said reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The American relay team won in seven minutes 13.99 seconds, the
quickest since another American side won the Seoul Olympics in
7:12.51.
</P>
<P>
Kurt Grote of the United States took the 100 breaststroke in
1:01.22.
</P>
<P>
Australian Samantha Riley swam away from South Africa's
world-record holder and Olympic gold medalist Penny Heyns to win
the women's 100 breaststroke in 1:07.81. Heyns finished second in
1:08.65.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 400 individual medley, Australian Matthew Dunn
overtook Canadian Curtis Myden in the last 20 meters to win in
4:16.11. Myden finished in 4:16.30.
</P>
<P>
The third Australian gold went to Michael Klim, who broke the
Australian and Commonwealth record he set in the morning heats to
win the men's 100 freestyle in 49.46. American Neil Walker clocked
49.50 for second.
</P>
<P>
American five-times Olympic gold medalist Jenny Thompson held
off Le Jingyi of China to win the women's 100 freestyle in 54.82.
</P>
<P>
Le, the world-recordholder and Olympic champion in the event,
finished in 54.86 after putting on a late surge to draw close to
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
Thompson also anchored the U.S. to victory in the women's 4x200
freestyle relay in 8:07.82, earning her 15th gold medal in five
Pan Pacific appearances.
</P>
<P>
The other U.S. gold went to Kristine Quance, who finished ahead
of teammate Madeline Crippen in the women's 400 individual medley
in 4:39.61.
</P>
<P>
About 300 swimmers are competing in the meet, which serves as
the warmup for the January's world championships in Perth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
