<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Opens More Ancient Tombs to Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Egypt is opening to visitors more
archeological tombs of Egyptian monarchs and top statesmen in
Luxor, an ancient city renowned for its rich historical relics,
about 750 kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by Egyptian Culture Minister and
Chairman of the Supreme Archeological Council Farouk Hosni here
today.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that among the most impressive tombs to be
opened in the Valley of the Kings in Luxor is that of King Seti II
who ruled Egypt from 1209 B.C. to 1205 B.C.
</P>
<P>
It is 74 meters long, and well-known for its most fascinating
inscriptions and colors, and relief scenes of the King,
skillfully sculptured and painted with bright colors which seem
almost intact until the present day.
</P>
<P>
So is the tomb of Queen Tausert who exclusively ruled Egypt
approximately in the year 1215 B.C., according to the Egyptian
culture minister.
</P>
<P>
He added that the restored tombs which will be opened in
November include that of a senior statesman called Roie. The tomb
is characterized by scenes of daily life such as tilling of soil,
yielding of flax crop and such religious rituals as funerals,
sacrifices as well as religious writings.
</P>
<P>
On the west bank of Luxor sit a rare and remarkable set of
tombs of top statesmen of ancient Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Medal Standings at Pan Pacific Swimming Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Following are the medal standings
of the Pan Pacific swimming championshipss after Monday's
competition in Fukuoka, Japan:
</P>
<P>
Country  gold  silver bronze  total
</P>
<P>
