<HEADLINE> France Again Expresses Worry Over Situation in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- France today described the
situation in southern Lebanon as "more and more worrying," as
Israeli troops and pro-Iranian Hezbollah guerrillas are continuing
their fighting there.
</P>
<P>
"The French government is following the evolution of the
situation and considers it more and more worrying," said French
Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen people, 14 of them Lebanese, were killed and 29 others,
three of them Israelis, wounded in the tit-for-tat attacks between
Israeli troops and Hezbollah guerrillas in one week's time.
</P>
<P>
"The number of the Lebanese victims and the fact that rockets
fell on the Israeli territories cannot but aggravate the tension,"
said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the French daily Le Monde, Lebanese Prime
Minister Rafic Hariri said that the tension in southern Lebanon is
linked with the "impasse" of relations between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Hariri also criticized Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat for
indirectly holding Lebanon responsible for the double-bombing
attack in Jerusalem at the end of last month.
</P>
<P>
Citing information from Israeli security, Arafat said on
Israeli television recently that the two terrorists who made the
attack "came from abroad."
</P>
<P>
Hariri also said that it could be the Palestinians who fired
the rockets which fell in northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Hezbollah rejected responsibility for the rocket attack
upon Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
