<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> None of 150 Possible Nazis on Swiss Bank List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Germany's center for the
investigation of Nazi crimes said today that some 150 names on the
list of dormant Holocaust-era accounts published by Swiss banks
could possibly be Nazis, but none of them were still wanted.
</P>
<P>
Willi Dressen, head of the Ludwigsburg-based organization, told
the German Press Agency dpa that the center was seeking further
information from the banks to confirm if these people were the
same as those on his files.
</P>
<P>
The center has found some 200 names on the list match those of
Nazi criminals, and some 50 of them, however, also identical with
Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
Dressen noted that none of the suspected Nazis on the list were
now still being sought for prosecution.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss Bankers Association in July published a list of 1,756
foreigners who had invested money in Switzerland before May 9,
1945 and had not been heard ever since, with a view to helping
trace heirs to the accounts held by Nazi victims during World War
II.
</P>
<P>
Experts have warned that the list could include names of Nazis
who secretly channeled funds to neutral Switzerland during the
war.
</P>
<P>
The dormant accounts are believed to worth 60.2 million Swiss
francs (some 40 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
