<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK Condemns Japanese Officials for Planning to Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) today strongly condemned a group of
Japanese cabinet members for planning to formally and collectively
pay respect to the Yasukuni Shrine which contains cinerary caskets
of some Japanese war criminals.
</P>
<P>
A commentary carried by the DPRK newspaper "Rodong Sinmun"
termed the plan as a farce, saying that the Yasukuni Shrine is a
place compiling the history of vicious Japanese militarism.
</P>
<P>
All the Asian people who were suffered from the Japanese
invasion during World War II have been condemning the Japanese
authorities for paying homage to the Yasukuni Shrine or seeking to
do so,
</P>
<P>
Paying respect to the Yasukuni Shrine hurts the Asian people's
hearts and is an action to seek to revive the militarism, it added.
</P>
<P>
So, paying homage to the Yasukuni Shrine is a political issue
which will show the direction of the development of Japanese
politics in the future, it noted.
</P>
<P>
The commentary pointed out that the Yasukuni Shrine has become
a stronghold of the Japanese militarists who want to spread the
idea of retaliation among the Japanese people and create the
atmosphere for reviving the militarism.
</P>
<P>
But in any case, the Japanese authorities cannot make the farce
legitimate and reasonable, it noted, adding that Japan cannot be
trusted by the world unless it learns the lesson from the history
and breaks with the mistakes committed in the past. 
</P>
</TEXT>
