<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Rate Gap in UK Widens to Worst for 50 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- People in Britain's big cities,
especially in the North, are increasingly likely to die before
people live in small towns, according to a new study of death
rates in Britain.
</P>
<P>
People living in areas with the highest mortality rates are now
almost twice as likely to die prematurely as those who live where
mortality rates are lowest -- the greatest degree of inequality.
</P>
<P>
Among the worst places are Glasgow, Manchester, Birmingham, and
urban Glamorganshire. The best are the small towns of Kent,
Surrey, Middlesex, Hertfordshire and Essex.
</P>
<P>
The figures have emerged in an analysis by Dr Daniel Dorling,
of the University of Bristol, in a report for the Joseph Rowntree
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
"Many people think life chances have been getting better all
the time, so to learn that we are more unequal than we were in the
1950s may be surprising," said the author.
</P>
<P>
Tessa Jowell, public health minister, has ordered a review of
health inequality by Sir Douglas Black, who first reported on the
issue in 1980. But almost all experts agree that little can be
done about it without first tackling inequality of income.
</P>
<P>
While there have been substantial improvements in survival, the
research found that one in 12 of the population now live in areas
where premature death rates are 15 percent above the national
average.
</P>
<P>
Differences in death rates cannot be blamed on factors such as
smoking alone because death rates among children show similar
divergences, meaning that where a child is born is more important
than ever in determining his or her chances of survival.
</P>
<P>
Dorling said it was "extremely unlikely" that Britain would be
able to meet a commitment, given under a World Health Organization
program in 1985, to cut health inequality as gauged by mortality
rates by a quarter by 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPCW to Inspect 35 Places in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Organization for the
Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) will inspect 35 places in
August to verify the implementation of the anti-chemical weaponry
convention.
</P>
<P>
OPCW specialists inspected another 30 places between June and
July and have planned more inspection tours for the near future,
according to an OPCW press release received here today.
</P>
<P>
The number of inspection tours was reported to the third
session of the OPCW Executive Council which took place in the
Hague from July 28 to August 1, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
OPCW specialists have up to 390 days after the signing of the
anti-chemical weaponry convention to verify the identity and
quantity of the chemical weaponry stocks to be destroyed and to
confirm such destruction.
</P>
<P>
A total of 98 countries and regions have ratified or acceded to
the convention while the Hague-based OPCW is waiting for another
69 countries and regions, which have signed the convention, to
ratify it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
