<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Workers Better Off Than Employees in Most EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Britain's average workers earn
more money back home than their counterparts in other leading
European Union (EU) countries, according to a survey published
today.
</P>
<P>
The survey, by the consultants Sedgwick Noble Lowndes and which
allows for differences in national pricing and purchasing
differences as well as tax and welfare contributions, placed
Britain in the fourth with its workers receiving the equivalent of
6.8 pounds (10.7 US dollars) an hour.
</P>
<P>
Luxembourg workers are top of the league with net hourly
earnings of 7.4 pounds (11.7 US dollars). Austria is in second
place at 7.1 pounds (11.2 US dollars), followed by Ireland at
seven pounds (11 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Germany is seventh at net level with hourly take-home pay of
6.5 pounds (10.3 US dollars), and France in eighth position at 6.3
pounds (10 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The survey said that outside Europe, the average Japanese
employee earns a net 8.9 pounds (14 US dollars) hourly, while the
US average is 6.9 pounds (10.9 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Deductions from gross earnings for UK workers are assessed at
an average of 25 percent, compared with 33 percent in Germany and
38 percent in Denmark, which reduce the higher salaries of their
employees to below the UK level.
</P>
<P>
David Formosa, international research manager at Sedgwick,
said, "For many years, the general impression has been that UK
employees enjoy a lower standard of living than in other parts of
central and northern Europe. This is certainly not borne out by
the figures."
</P>
<P>
"Other countries may offer higher gross salaries but this does
not mean that their citizens are always better off," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Government Intervenes UPS Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- After a week of Teamsters
strike against UPS, the U.S. government began to intervene the
dispute today as Labor Secretary Alexis Herman called on both
sides to meet with her and find a way to get back to the
negotiation table.
</P>
<P>
"I've asked the leaders of the Teamsters union and the United
Parcel Service to meet with me today at the Labor Department and
they have both agreed," Herman said in a statement early today.
</P>
<P>
"I intend to talk with each party individually to find out what
it will take to move these talks forward and to urge greater
flexibility and a willingness to compromise to get back to the
bargaining table," she said.
</P>
<P>
Herman told NBC's "Meet the Press" Sunday, "The president
recognizes that these are serious issues: the nature of part-time
work, pension protection for American workers. These are all
issues that we care about."
</P>
<P>
UPS Vice Chairman John Alden said today on ABC's "Good Morning
America" that he could not promise anything when asked if UPS
would hire replacements for strikers.
</P>
<P>
"Right now we have no plans to hire people. We would like our
people to come back to work. I can't promise what the future will
bring," he said.
</P>
<P>
Herman asked the two sides not to "escalate this strike" and
said hiring replacements for the 185,000 striking union members
"does contribute to that escalation."
</P>
<P>
Teamsters President Ron Carey said on CBS on Sunday that "I
think he would have a problem" if the company did hire
replacements."
</P>
<P>
The dispute focuses on two issues: the company's demand to
withdraw from the Teamsters' multi-employer pension plan and the
union's call to convert thousands of part-time jobs into full-time
ones.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-eight percent of UPS employees work part time, and there
hasn't been an increase in their base wage of eight dollars an
hour since 1982, much lower than the full-time employees.
</P>
<P>
UPS normally handles 12 million parcels and letters daily. The
work stoppage's damage to small businesses' operations throughout
the country has governors and business leaders clamoring for White
House intervention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
