<HEADLINE> Peace Process Not Restricted to Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa reaffirmed today that the peace process is not restricted
to the security issue.
</P>
<P>
Moussa made the statement to reporters after having received a
phone call from U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross who is currently
continuing his intensive shuttle diplomacy between the Israelis
and Palestinians, according to the Egyptian Middle East News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said that the security issue is important to both the
Palestinians and Israelis, and the implementation of the
signed agreements is also very important.
</P>
<P>
Moussa indicated that the peace process is not restricted to
the security issue, though it constitutes one of the obstacles
that have to be overcome and settled.
</P>
<P>
The peace process, he added, embraces other issues as well,
such as settlements and the final phase negotiations, because
these issues constitute the core of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Moussa also reiterated the importance of restoring confidence
between the Palestinian and Israeli sides, pointing out that
the peace process needs to regain the confidence of the whole
region.
</P>
<P>
Ross is currently endeavoring to restore confidence between
the Palestinian and Israeli sides with regard to security
issues, Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the hope that U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright would undertake, during her forthcoming Middle
East tour which is due to take place either at the end of this
month or early next month, all aspects of the strategic peace
issue.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Moussa met here today with U.S. Ambassador in Cairo
Edward Walker to discuss Ross's current mission in the region and
the ongoing efforts to resume peace negotiations between the
Palestinian and Israeli sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
