<HEADLINE> SADC Trade Ministers to Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 11 (Xinhua)-- Trade ministers of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) will meet in
Tanzania's capital Dar es Salaam later this week to discuss a
proposed protocal on a free trade area.
</P>
<P>
SADC's Executive Seeretary Kaire Mbuende said today in
Windhock that the meeting will focus on tariff reduction on
goods traded within the 12-member regional organisation.
</P>
<P>
Local media quoted the SADC chief as saying that once the
agreement is implemented, goods produced in a member state
will move freely into others without tariffs.
</P>
<P>
Recommendations from the trade ministers' meeting will first
be discussed by a SADC council of ministers before submission
to their heads of state and government for approval.
</P>
<P>
Currently heavy tariffs are placed on goods from SADC nations
which are not members of the Southern African Customs Union
whenever they are sold within member states.
</P>
<P>
The customs union comprises Botswana, lesotho, Namibia
South Africa and Swaziland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
