<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Africa to Set Up Regional Seas Program Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 11 (Xinhua) -- A Regional Coordinating Unit
(RCU) for the Eastern African Regional Seas Program is scheduled
to be set up on August 12 on St. Anne Island in the Seychelles in
a bid to solve trans-boundary marine problems.
</P>
<P>
A news release issued here today by the United Nations
Environment Program (UNEP) said that Elizabeth Dowdeswell, UNEP
Executive Director, will officially open the RCU which will host
the secretariat for the Nairobi Convention.
</P>
<P>
The release quoted the UNEP director as saying that the
protection of the Eastern African marine environment is a shared
responsibility of the coast countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
"The coastal zone from Somalia to Mozambique is home to some
25 million people and we need joint action to tackle serious
trans-boundary marine problems such as pollution and the
protection of endangered plants and animals," she noted.
</P>
<P>
From July 27 to August 1, the UNEP and the RCU held in Nairobi
the first meeting of a Global Environment Facility funded project
to facilitate regional dialogue and cooperation on trans-boundary
problems in the international waters.
</P>
<P>
The second meeting to discuss the project will be held in the
Seychelles in March, 1999, according to the release.
</P>
<P>
The RCU will be formed in accordance with the Nairobi Convention,
adopted in Nairobi in june 1985 and entered into force on May
30, 1996. The convention calls for Protection, Management and
Development of the Marine and Coastal Environment of the Eastern
Africa Region.
</P>
<P>
To date, Comoros, Kenya, Mauritius, Reunion, Mozambique,
Seychelles, Somalia and Tanzania have ratified the Nairobi
Convention.
</P>
<P>
Madagascar is expected to ratify the convention soon while
South Africa has shown interest in participating. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
