<HEADLINE> EU to Send Anti-Terrorism Expert to Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 11 (Xinhua) -- In an attempt to assert its
role in the peace process, the European Union (EU) will send an
expert to help the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) fight
against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with PNA President Yasser Arafat in
Ramallah, West Bank this morning, EU special envoy to the Middle
East Miguel Moratinos, raised the proposal, according to a report
of JMCC, a Palestinian press service based in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos told reporters after the meeting that "the EU is
offering the PNA a special coordination, a special assistance for
fighting terror."
</P>
<P>
He said that a Swedish expert will be coming and assist the
Palestinians in order to get rid of violence and terrorism in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos made the overture while U.S. Middle East peace
coordinator Dennis Ross was trying hard to push the Israelis and
Palestinians to restore peace talks by pressuring the PNA to
accept security cooperation as a prerequisite.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinians demanded that any resumption of peace
talks involve discussions on other major outstanding issues,
especially the Israeli policy of settlement expansion.
</P>
<P>
When asked by reporters about the EU proposal, Arafat's
advisor Nabil Abu Redeineh suggested that they should "ask
Moratinos what is meant by sending an expert."
</P>
<P>
"We are not in need for anything," he said. "We are
fulfilling our duties and committed to them and we demand the
other party's commitment."
</P>
<P>
Later in Jerusalem, Moratinos met with Ross, who briefed him
on his discussions with Israeli and Palestinian leaders in his
shuttle diplomacy. 
</P>
