<HEADLINE> Guinean, S. Leonean Leaders to Meet on Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 10 (Xinhua) --The Sierra Leonean military leader
is expected to meet the Guinean president soon on the resumption
of the failed Abidjan talks between the Sierra Leonean junta and
west African countries, said a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Saidu Momoh, former Sierra Leonean president overthrown
in a coup five years ago, said the Sierran Leonean military
government had received an invitation from Guinean President
Lansana Conte for the meeting expected to take place within this
week.
</P>
<P>
Momoh was called back from exile by ousted President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah to help restart the peace talks which collapsed at
the end of last month in Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire, after the junta
leader Johnny Koroma said he would stay in power until 2001.
</P>
<P>
A British Broadcasting Company report today quoted Momoh as
saying that he had met both Conte and Koroma who are interested
to resolve the present impasse in Sierra Leone through talks.
</P>
<P>
Momoh said that President Conte had told him that he would
like to meet Koroma anywhere at any time. No matter president
Conte will go to Freetown or not, "I'm sure Koroma should be
prepared to go to the meeting", he added.
</P>
<P>
After Koroma's announcement in which he said he would stay in
power unitil 2001, the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) has tightened blockade of Sierra Leone in a bid to
remove the junta from power.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS has vowed to restore Kabbah's government through three
measures, namely, negotiations, sanctions and the use of force.
</P>
<P>
Momoh said he was totally opposed to military actions to
resolve the crisis in Sierra Leone, which would lead to
destruction rather than other results.
</P>
<P>
The former president, who has been accused of having a hand in
the May 25 coup that toppled Kabbah's government, said he hoped a
negotiated settlement of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
It is still early to know what effect this meeting would
produce, but observers are expecting improvement in the political
situation in Sierra Leone in the next couple of weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
