<HEADLINE> Illegal Weapons Seized in S. Africa-Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Police forces from South
Africa and Mozambique have found and destroyed thousands of guns
and millions of rounds of ammunition in Mozambique in a joint
military operation, sources reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
Rag Crewe, spokesman for the South Africa Police Service
(SAPS), said in a statement earlier that during the joint operation,
dubbed "Rachel 111" between July 21 and the end of the last week,
police discovered more than 5500 machine guns, sub machine guns
and automatic rifles.
</P>
<P>
Among them, 1177 were AK47 rifles and 78 were pistols,
sources close to the war game said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that firearms and other weapons were being
smuggled into South Africa from Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
These firearms were being used in the on-going taxi violence,
armed robberies, vehicle hijackings and other crimes, Crewe said,
that the arms caches in Mozambique had to be destroyed to curb
crimes in both countries.
</P>
<P>
Also found were 518 anti-personnel mines, four landmines, 336
grenades, 153 detonators, more than 3726 mortar bombs, 76 rocket
and mortar launchers, 2340 projectiles, 13 cannons and about three
million rounds of ammunition of various calibres and four
magazines.
</P>
<P>
Crewe said SAPS members involved in the operation were drawn
from various divisions, including the bomb disposal and research
unit, the special task force, the internal security unit, the
firearm unit and the national detective service.
</P>
<P>
"This (war game) should have a positive impact on the flow of
illegal weapons across our border," Crewe said. "Similar types of
operations will be conducted in future and may even be broadered,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
