<HEADLINE> China Views Right to Development As Most Vital Right </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese human rights expert
said here today the realization of the right to development is the
only way to ensure the basic needs of most people in the world.
</P>
<P>
Zhong Shukong, an alternate member of the Sub-Commission on
Prevention of Discrimination and Protection of Minorities, made
the remarks at the 49th session of the organization which is under
the United Nations Human Rights Committee.
</P>
<P>
Zhong warned that there exists great inequities between
developed and developing countries. Poverty and backwardness left
over by history remain serious constraints to the socio-economic
development efforts of 78 percent of the world's people, he said.
</P>
<P>
Reports submitted to the session held on August 4-29 show that
the worldwide population of the poor increased to 1.5 billion in
1996. Ninety percent of them were in the developing countries,
with "an income of less than one dollar per capita per day."
</P>
<P>
Zhong accused some wealthy countries of turning a blind eye to
the miserable life of the poor populations in the world, while
criticizing their human rights conditions.
</P>
<P>
He urged the developed countries to help the developing ones
with their socio-economic development, so as to erase imbalances
and inequities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
