<HEADLINE> New Housing Price Index Up in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The new housing price index in
Canada increased by 1.0 percent in June compared with the same
period a year earlier, Statistics Canada said today.
</P>
<P>
June is the fourth consecutive month for which the index has
registered an annual increase, after 31 consecutive decreases
since July 1994.
</P>
<P>
The index increased 0.1 percent from May to June 1997, the
federal statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
"The general improvement in housing markets in recent months
has been attributable to higher consumer confidence and favorable
interest rates," the agency noted.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the competitive nature of housing markets has moderated
price increases or caused decreases in some of the cities
surveyed.
</P>
<P>
"The outlook for future housing construction seems
encouraging," it added.
</P>
<P>
Housing construction intentions were up 22.0 percent for the
first six months of 1997 compared with 1996. In the meantime,
housing starts were up 26.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian Real Estate Association reported that this year's
first-half resale transactions were up 17.9 percent from the same
period last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
