<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Inflation at 2-Year High in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The headline annual rate of
inflation in Britain leapt to a near two-year high of 3.3 percent
in July from 2.9 percent in June, showed official figures today.
</P>
<P>
July's rise in the headline inflation rate was largely due to
rises in housing and motoring costs, the Office of National
Statistics said.
</P>
<P>
The figures showed the cost of driving to have risen by 1
percent over the month, and housing inflation to have climbed 1.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
The ONS also pointed to an upward pressure from seasonal food
prices. Heavy rain in June had led to a shortage of some fruit
crops, which had fed through to price rises, it added.
</P>
<P>
The office said the underlying rate of inflation, which
excludes volatile mortgage payments, jumped too. It reached 3.0
percent in July from 2.7 percent in June, well above the
government's 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, a jump in the annual rate of inflation is not likely
to lead to another rise in interest rates, analysts believe.
</P>
<P>
Simon Briscos, of Nikko Europe, said the influence of the data
on rate decision should be limited.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Bank of England said current levels of base
rates were "consistent" with the inflation target.
</P>
<P>
Roger Bootle, of HSBC, said the underlying picture showed that
inflation had hardly moved at all. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
