<HEADLINE> OAU Envoy: Separatism in Comoros "Totally Unacceptable" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The special envoy of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) for the Comoros, Pierre Yere,
today told the separatists on the Comoran island of Anjouan that
it is "totally unacceptable" for them to destroy the Indian Ocean
nation.
</P>
<P>
The Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted Yere as saying that the
OAU is ready to help find a solution to the crisis in the Comoros
but not in an "insurrectional atmosphere."
</P>
<P>
A group of separatists in Anjouan last week declared their
island "independent" and asked for the return of French rule, and
the neighboring island of Moheli followed suit.
</P>
<P>
Yere, who is ambassador of Cote d'Ivoire to Ethiopia, told the
"president" of Anjouan, Aballah Ibrahim, that it is too late to
"go back in the course of history" and "return to the French
colonial period."
</P>
<P>
"We don't have the right to choose chaos and the destruction of
this country. Secession is unrealistic and totally unacceptable,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Federal Republic of Comoros consists of the Great
Comoro island, Anjouan and Moheli. The fourth island of the
archipelago, Mayotte, has been under French rule since the
independence of the Comoros in 1975.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, a Mayotte deputy from Mayotte of the
French National Assembly, Henri Jean-Baptiste, today asked France
to take "an initiative" supporting talks among different parties
of the Comoros.
</P>
<P>
France has condemned the separatism of Anjouan and called on
the Comorans to find a solution to their country's crisis through
talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
