<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets U.S. House Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIDAIHE, August 12 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin, meeting
with Benjamin Gilman, chairman of the U.S. House of
Representatives' International Relations Committee, today said
there is great potential for China-U.S. co-operation in
maintaining global and regional peace.
</P>
<P>
The two countries can develop their economic ties and promote
economic growth and prosperity of the world, Jiang said, and that
they have major common interests in spite of great changes in the
international situation after the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
China has always placed great importance on its relations with
the U.S. and has made consistent efforts to improve and develop
the relations, he added.
</P>
<P>
The two countries should keep the fundamental interests of
their people in mind from a strategic perspective when
strengthening exchanges, Jiang pointed out, and said they should
increase mutual understanding, expand cooperation and seek common
ground while keeping their own differences.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that China and the U.S. will act in
keeping with the three joint communiques and raise their relations
to a new level, and that the U.S. Congress will be more active in
bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Gilman said this year witnesses the 25th birthday of the
Shanghai Communique, and that the two countries need to increase
exchanges and understanding, and to build a bridge of friendship
between them.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and China share many common interests in the
present-day international situation, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that U.S. and China will make
contributions to regional and global peace, stability and
prosperity, and that the Congress is willing to forge closer ties
with China, and hopes that the 21st century will be a co-operative
one for the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Congress and the American people are looking forward to
Jiang's visit this fall, he said, and that he is confident that
the trip will be of great importance to the growth of bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation are here at the invitation of the Foreign
Affairs Committee of the Chinese National People's Congress.
</P>
