<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Lodges Protest to U.N. over Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has formally lodged
protest to the United Nations against an agreement on partial
integration between Turkey and the Turkish Cypriot regime in
Cyprus, Cyprus News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The association agreement, which was signed last week during a
visit to the Turkish-controlled northern part of Cyprus by
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem, calls for "gradual economic
and financial integration and partial integration on security,
defense and foreign policy matters."
</P>
<P>
It came following a recent European Union (EU) reconfirmation
that accession talks with Cyprus will begin next year.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Cyprus'
Permanent Representative to the U.N. Nicos Agathocleous stressed
that this provocative action took place only five days before
the commencement of the second round of inter-communal talks on
Cyprus under U.N. auspices in Switzerland, which began Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said the agreement constitutes "a policy of blackmail" and
"undermines the on-going efforts of the international community
to reach a solution to the Cyprus problem."
</P>
<P>
Agathocleous noted that "these illegal and condemnable actions
by Turkey, which are aimed at institutionalizing and
consolidating the de facto partition of Cyprus - enforced by the
Turkish occupation forces - and the integration of the occupied
areas into Turkey, are in contravention of the provisions of the
U.N. Charter and relevant U.N. resolutions and decisions on
Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot ambassador also pointed out that the timing and
the manner of the Turkish move demonstrate Turkey's lack of
political will for a settlement in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the Cypriot government's intention to take part
in the peace talks with good faith, political will and
determination to achieve a solution.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unsolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops invaded and took over
the northern third in the wake of a short-lived Greek Cypriot
coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
