<HEADLINE> German Linked to Versace Murder Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The fugitive German owner of a
Miami beach houseboat used by the suspected murderer of fashion
guru Gianni Versace has been arrested in Germany on charges of
fraud and tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
Leipzig based prosecutor Norbert Roeger confirmed today that
Torsten Reineck, 49, wanted in Germany since 1993, was arrested
when he arrived at the Frankfurt Airport on Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that Reineck's arrest had no connection with
Versace killing, but rather resulted from charges involving up to
111,000 U.S. dollars of fraud.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier German press reports, Reineck moved from
Hamburg to Leipzig after the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, and
opened a gambling house there. He also bought into the Leipzig
brewery "Leo-Braeu" which later went bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the fraud charge, Reineck was also under
investigation for evasion of nearly 280,000 dollars in taxes, the
German Bild newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The suspected killer of Versace, Andrew Cunanan, shot himself
to death on Reineck's houseboat on July 24, putting an end a
three-month-long manhunt in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) was reported to
have also ruled out Reineck's connection with Versace's slaying
after questioning Reineck following Cunanan's death. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
