<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reviving China's Largest City With Deng's Theory (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In accordance with Deng's strategic decision, Jiang Zemin, in
his report at the 14th CPC National Congress, said that Shanghai
should become one of the international economic, financial and
trade centers and play a leading role in the economic growth of
regions along the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
This affirms the strategic importance of Shanghai in China's
reforms and opening up drive, and has meant momentous changes. The
city has since given priority to developing urban infrastructure,
tertiary industry, and high-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
It has also placed much emphasis on developing the financial
sector. In the past five years, its financial sector has achieved
extraordinarily rapid growth, and it now has a financial system
consisting of specialized banks, commercial banks, foreign-funded
banks, local banks, cooperative banks, trust companies and
insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
At present, 210 foreign-funded financial institutions are
operating in Shanghai, which have provided powerful financial
support for construction and development.
</P>
<P>
As early as the 1980s, Jiang Zemin, who was then working in
Shanghai, organized several major discussions on emancipating the
minds of Shanghai people to encourage them to get rid of any
restraints.
</P>
<P>
In his last visit to Shanghai in 1994, Deng told senior
municipal leaders: "You must seize the last few years of the 20th
century. This is Shanghai's last opportunity."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reviving China's Largest City With Deng's Theory (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The people of Shanghai regard the opening up and development of
the Pudong area east of the Huangpu River as the most significant
opportunity of the 1990s. The area has completed its ten major
infrastructure projects two years ahead of schedule, while the
economy has maintained a growth rate twice that of the Puxi,
a development area to the west of the Huangpu.
</P>
<P>
One of Shanghai's development strategy is to make full use of
resources and capital from both domestic and international sources
and explore both the domestic and international markets.
</P>
<P>
From 1994 to 1996, the amount of foreign investment in Shanghai
exceeded 10 billion US dollars worth, while the city's exports
kept growing faster than the GNP.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has also led the country in reforming state-owned
enterprises and introducing a modern enterprise system, which are
regarded as the primary task of establishing a socialist market
economy.
</P>
<P>
The city has succeeded in urban construction and renovating the
old city, with many business and commercial districts in the
downtown areas and new industrial zones in the suburbs. More than
two million residents have moved into new housing, markedly
improving their living conditions and quality of life.
</P>
<P>
So, guided by the theory of a great man, Shanghai has set out
on a journey to a great future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
