<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Commissioner Stresses on Humanitarian Aid to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- European Humanitarian
Commissioner Emma Bonino today described the correct and full
implementation of the oil-for-food program as being in the
interests of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
On returning from her trip to Iraq, Bonino told reporters that
the distribution of food and medicine was not satisfactory in
northern Iraq compared with that in the central and southern parts
of the country, though situation in the north where most of the
Kurds lived was favorable.
</P>
<P>
"Imagine how dramatic a change international donations can make
toward the day-by-day life of the Iraqi people," she said. She
cited the 214.9 million ECU European Union's (EU) humanitarian
office had contributed to Iraq since 1991.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, with a population of 21 million, has so far received
humanitarian assistance amounting to 4.6 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
But the commissioner blamed uneven distribution in Iraq for
hampering the implementation of the humanitarian aid program.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council approved the 986 Resolution
in February 1996 and the oil-for-food program started to be
implemented in February this year.
</P>
<P>
"The distribution of food goes on pretty well, but the
distribution of medicine is completely another matter," said the
commissioner who found a shortage of medicine in the country.
</P>
<P>
Bonino said the aid program for the next six months had to be
well targeted.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner made the trip after the United Nations
approved a new contract for Iraq to export, over the next six
months, 2.3 billion dollars worth of oil in exchange for food,
medicine and drinking water as well as other humanitarian
materials.
</P>
<P>
She said that during their meeting in Baghdad, Iraqi Deputy
Prime Minister Tariq Aziz appealed to EU countries to help have
the U.N.-imposed embargo lifted. The embargo was imposed
following Iraq's invasion of neighboring Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner quoted Aziz as saying that the embargo only
benefits Britain and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. will lift the embargo only after Iraq eliminates its
weaponry of mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam, Laos to Strengthen Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese Prime Minister Vo Van
Kiet arrived in Vientiane today for a three-day visit to Laos,
which is aimed at improving the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The leading Vietnamese newspapers today carried editorials,
hailing Kiet's visit as "an important event marking a new step in
the development of friendship and comprehensive cooperation
between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
Vietnam and Laos commemorated the 20th anniversary of the
signing of a friendship and cooperation treaty between them in
July. 
</P>
