<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Firms Optimistic About Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Most of the Japanese firms
surveyed by a influential newspaper say they believe the country's
economy is gradually recovering.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-five of the 100 big manufacturers surveyed by Yomiuri
Shimbun said they believed economy was slowly improving, and only
39 manufacturers said economy remained the same.
</P>
<P>
Most of the firms attributed the improvement to a weaker yen,
bigger exports and continued low interest rates. Japanese interest
rates have been at record low for more than a year to promote
economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-one of the firms surveyed predicted their income and net
profits this year would increase sharply over those of last year.
</P>
<P>
The government declared in February 1996 that the nation's
economy had finally come out of the slump that followed the
collapse of the "bubble" economy in the early 1990s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
