<HEADLINE> Anti-Israeli Protest Continues in West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Some 2,000 Palestinians
marched in the West Bank city of Nablus today to protest against
Israeli punitive measures against the Palestinians taken after the
suicide bombing attacks in Jerusalem on July 30.
</P>
<P>
During the march, organized by national and Islamic
organizations, the protesters carrying Palestinian and Arab flags
and chanting anti-Israeli slogans, proceeded from the city center
to the Nablus Govererorate, according to a report of JMCC, an
East Jerusalem-based Palestinian press service.
</P>
<P>
The angry demonstrators also burned effigies of Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and U.S. Middle East peace envoy
Dennis Ross. They also called for national unity.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians were reportedly exasperated by what they
called Ross's pro-Israeli attitude in his current shuttle
diplomacy between Israeli and Palestinian leaders.
</P>
<P>
Ross made it clear that his current mission was aimed at
keeping the focus of his talks with both sides on the need
for effective security measures against terrorist attacks, while
seeking to foster "an atmosphere of partnership" between Israeli
and Palestinian officials.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, thousands of Palestinian protesters marched down
Gaza's main street and in the West Bank city of Ramallah,
thousands more demonstrated as some headed toward the Israeli
military checkpoint before being stopped by Palestinian police.
</P>
<P>
The protesters in Gaza demanded Israel free prisoners and the
11-day total closure imposed since the double suicide bombing in
Jerusalem on July 30, in which 15 people were killed and 170
others wounded. They also expressed their strong support in their
slogans for Palestinian President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
In Ramallah, some demonstrators burned the Israeli flags
during their procession.
</P>
<P>
Israel banned Palestinians or commerce from entering Israel
after the bombing in Jerusalem. A ban on travel between some
Palestinian towns in the West Bank is still in force and Israel
has refused to pass on 70 million U.S. dollars in tax revenues to
the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
