<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Sell More Public Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
identified 219 public enterprises to be sold to private owners,
among which 82 enterprises would be put on sale during the current
fiscal year starting from July, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
According to the ambitious program, the buyers would be free to
request the Privatization Board (PB) to float tenders for the sale
of any unit they select from this list.
</P>
<P>
During the fiscal 1996-97, the government only finalized the
sale of 17 enterprises out of a list of 61 which were put on sale
and in the last four years only 12 state-owned enterprises (SOEs)
have been privatized.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the PB, however, said that opposition by labor
unions, local political influences and vested interests of the
bureaucrats were the main problems in the way of the privatization
of the SOEs.
</P>
<P>
"The organized laborers have wrong notions about privatization
and fear loss of jobs. Much of their demands are impossible to
meet and those are intended to agitate laborers in the specific
enterprises," said Kazi Zafarullah, chairman of the PB.
</P>
<P>
"The bureaucrats are also an obstacle because they lose many
facilities if enterprises are privatized. Therefore,
over-valuation of enterprises is deliberately done to discourage
privatization," Zafarullah said.
</P>
<P>
To accelerate the privatization process, the PB is expected to
be reorganized soon with the inclusion of six members of
parliament, both from Treasury and opposition bench, and
representatives from different trades and professional bodies,
said official sources.
</P>
<P>
Another move has also been taken to allow the PB to make a
final decision on the sale of enterprises worth up to 100 million
taka (about 2.2 million U.S. dollars), the sources added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
