<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan police have arrested 30
suspects in connection with the killing of two police officers
during last Friday's strike called by opposition parties, the
"Kenya Times" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday part of the crowd attending the pro-reforms rally
at Central Park in Nairobi lynched Special Branch Constable
Gilbert Simiyu.
</P>
<P>
The second policeman was driving to his Wangige home when a
rowdy crowd hit his car with stones and was killed when his car
landed in a ditch where the killers followed him with more
stones.
</P>
<P>
Police sources at Kikuyu town, about 20 kilometers southwest
of Nairobi, told the paper that the suspects were helping police
with investigations over the stoning murder of Police Inspector
Francis Ngugi.
</P>
<P>
The "Daily Nation" today reported that four people from the
opposition National Development Party (NDP) were arrested Monday
over the killing of the policeman in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday night, police arrested a personal aide of NDP
leader Raila Odinga, Tom Adinda, who is still in custody.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Police Commissioner Duncan Wachira last week ordered a
nationwide crackdown on all forms of lawlessness and launched a
major manhunt for the killers of two police officers.
</P>
<P>
Wachira stressed that all acts of lawlessness would be met
with the full force of the law and "we will do everything within
its powers" to apprehend the perpetrators of the two killings.
</P>
