<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Opposition Accuses Gov't of Selling out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Leader of the opposition
Bangladesh Nationalist party (BNP) Khaleda Zia today accused the
government of selling out the country's sovereignty to its
neighboring India.
</P>
<P>
"When we speak about sell-out of our country, the government
says that a country is not a salable commodity like potatoes and
carrots. True, the land mass of our country is not being
transferred elsewhere, but its sovereignty is being compromised,"
said Khaleda.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Khaleda claimed that the
government is selling out the country in such areas as economy,
foreign relations and defense. "Finally the country's cultural
identity is being submerged with an alien culture."
</P>
<P>
She said India is still sheltering Bangladesh's insurgents and
has been engaged in an environmental aggression by denying
Bangladesh's rightful share of Ganges water and of other common
rivers.
</P>
<P>
"The ruling Awami (people's) League (AL) hurriedly signed a
Ganges water-sharing treaty that turned out to be a hoax. In the
first dry season after the inking of the treaty, Bangladesh got an
all-time low quantum of water," said the opposition leader, who
lost the general election in June last year.
</P>
<P>
The former Prime Minister also denied the AL's allegations that
her party did not raise such contentious issues with India while
in power.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the opposition leader said her party would like to
expand economic and ecological cooperation with India for common
good.
</P>
<P>
"But that cannot be one-way traffic. We want a dialogue with
India on all the contentious issues and a settlement on honorable
and equitable terms," said Khaleda.
</P>
<P>
During the one-hour press conference, Khaleda claimed that
about 200 of her party's workers were killed during the past year
while thousands of opposition activists were languishing in prison
without trial or on false charges.
</P>
<P>
The country's economy is in ruins and foreign investors were
also being scared away, she said.
</P>
<P>
"Under the circumstances, we call upon the ruling party to come
out an a clean slate and to refrain from ruination of the national
economy. Or else we shall be forced to move for change of
government through democratic process," the opposition leader
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
