<HEADLINE> Estonia Threatens Water Supply to Russian Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Estonia warned the Russian town
of Ivangorod on Monday that it would cut the town's water supply
if it did not settle a debt to the Estonian suppliers.
</P>
<P>
Itar-Tass news agency reported today from Tallinn, capital of
Estonia, that the warning was made by the leadership of the Narva
canal, which is within Estonia.
</P>
<P>
The Estonian suppliers required that the Ivangorod authorities
submit a schedule for the repayment of the three-month-old debt of
seven million crowns (about 473,000 U.S. dollars) to them by the
end of this week.
</P>
<P>
Ivangorod is in the Leningrad region and separated by a river
from Estonia's Narva. During the Soviet era, these two towns
shared a single infrastructure, including the water supply and
sewerage systems.
</P>
<P>
All water-intake facilities remained on the Estonian side after
the collapse of the USSR, and Ivangorod had to import drinking
water from sovereign Estonia.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that at the beginning of the year, Narva had
already cut water to Ivangorod by half, and threatened to cut it
altogether.
</P>
<P>
The situation was moderated by the Estonian government, which
allocated 3.3 million Estonian crowns (about 230,000 U.S. dollars)
to pay its neighbor's debt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
