<HEADLINE> Sweden's State Debt Begins to Shrink </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Swedish National Debt
Office said Monday the state debt in July dropped 600 million
Swedish kronor (about 75 million U.S. dollars) to 1,438 billion
Kronor (about 180 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
This is the first time in seven years the state debt has
decreased.
</P>
<P>
In the full year of 1998, the Swedish state debt is estimated
to decline 10 billion kronor (about 1.25 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Director of the Swedish National Debt Office Thomas Franzen
said that the 1998 budget surplus should be used to pay off state
loans.
</P>
<P>
After the 1998 election year, a Social Democratic government
would spend more on battling unemployment and resuming previously
axed welfare benefits, while a Conservative government would push
for tax cuts, observers said. 
