<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Inflation to Fall to 6 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's inflation rate is
expected to fall to six percent this year after the implementation
of the new tight money policy in an effort to control sharp
fluctuation in the money market, an Indonesian official said
today.
</P>
<P>
"This year's inflation rate is expected to drop to six percent
from 6.47 percent in 1996 with the low inflation rate in the first
half of this year," chief of the Central Bureau of Statistics,
Sugito Suwito, told a seminar on human resources development.
</P>
<P>
Sugito said that a tight money policy will usually force down
inflation as there is less money in the market.
</P>
<P>
In 1992 the government issued a similar policy which helped
bring down the inflation rate to below five percent.
</P>
<P>
This year's drought, on the other hand, has the potential to
fuel the country's inflation, while the impact of rupiah
(Indonesian currency) depreciation is not seen yet.
</P>
<P>
While the tight money policy would not have a negative impact
on inflation, Sugito admitted that it would affect the country's
economic growth which was expected to drop.
</P>
<P>
He declined to predict the economic growth figure, saying only
that it would depend on how long the new policy would be in force.
</P>
<P>
The country's economic growth last year was 7.82 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
