<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reviving China's Largest City With Deng's Theory (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Since 1992, Shanghai, China's
largest city, has seen the most incredible development in its
history.
</P>
<P>
In the five years since the 14th National Congress of the
Communist Party of China (CPC), the city's gross domestic product
(GDP) has seen average annual growth of more than 14 percent,
double the rate for the previous five years. Per capita GNP also
surged to over 3,000 US dollars from about 1,000 US dollars five
years ago.
</P>
<P>
With new bridges over the Huangpu River, skyscrapers towering
aloft, and massive infrastructure construction underway
everywhere, Shanghai is said to be, in the words of United Nations
officials, "one of the world's most vibrant cities".
</P>
<P>
The city attributes the tremendous changes to the theory of
building socialism with Chinese characteristics put forward by Deng
Xiaoping, late Chinese leader who passed away in February of this
year, as well as to the leadership of the CPC Central Committee
with Jiang Zemin at the core.
</P>
<P>
Following the decision in the 1980s to open a number of coastal
cities and special economic zones to the outside world, Deng began
to focus his attention on Shanghai in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
"Promoting Shanghai's development is a significant step," he
was quoted as saying, and "Shanghai is our trump card, and it will
become easier for us to develop China if we first develop
Shanghai."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the center of the global economy was
shifting toward the Asia-Pacific region, and that Shanghai in the
past had been the most cosmopolitan city in east Asia.
</P>
<P>
"We must use Shanghai as a base to promote the development of
the whole Yangtze River Delta and other regions along the
Yangtze," he stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Weaker banking shares pushed
the Australian share market to close on a lower note today.
</P>
<P>
"The banks most definitely have driven the recent fall," Scott
Foster and Partners senior adviser Julian Gregory said.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index was down 16.7 points at 2650.5,
building on Monday's 1.6 percent decline.
</P>
<P>
Gregory said that investors were taking profits in banks amid
fears that Wall Street could fall again after it dropped sharply
Friday and Monday before bargain hunters moved in.
</P>
<P>
The banks index today was 75.9 points lower at 5020.7, with the
Commonwealth diving 28 cents, ANZ Bank down 23 cents, National
Australia Bank falling 19 cents and Westpac Bank slipping 15 cents
a share.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index was 34.5 points lower at 4266.5 and
the all resources index was 1.8 points softer at 1390.3.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere among industrial shares, soft drink giant Coco Cola
Amatil dipped 35 cents building on a recent downward trend sparked
by concerns over the group's European operations.
</P>
<P>
The gold index lifted 13.1 points to 1302.0 while the precious
metal closed at 327.70 U.S. dollars an ounce, up from 326.25
previously.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 306.9 million shares worth 853.45
million Australian dollars (631.55 million U.S. dollars) with
falls of 599 beating rises of 468.  
</P>
