<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Finishes Firm Against U.S. Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar finished
firmer today against the U.S. currency as the financial markets
cautiously awaited the words of Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA)
Governor Ian Macfarlane.
</P>
<P>
The governor is to address a dinner party of the Australian
Institute of Company Directors in Perth tonight.
</P>
<P>
Westpac Banking Corp economist Katharine Hole said the speech
would be of interest as Macfarlane had made few public comments
recently.
</P>
<P>
"Of particular note will be whether the governor makes comments
aimed at encouraging or discouraging expectations for further
easing," she said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished firmer at 73.88 U.S. cents up
from yesterday's 73.68 cents close, but well below its day high of
74.08.
</P>
<P>
The currency began modestly higher this morning, after being
bought up to just below 74.00 cents offshore overnight on the back
of options plays by market participants.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar ended at 85.80 from
84.84 against yen and at 1.3815 from 1.3639 against marks.
</P>
</TEXT>
