<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Send More Students Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Some 3,420 people will have a
chance to go abroad to study at state expense next year, 1,000
more than this year, sources from China's State Education
Commission (SEC) say.
</P>
<P>
Of these, 23 percent will do research as senior visiting
scholars, while the others will study engineering, science, arts,
and medicine, said an official from the National Scholarship
Council for International Studies (NSCIS).
</P>
<P>
NSCIS, which handles applications for international studies on
behalf of the SEC, received a total of 40,000 applications for
next year's study at state expense.
</P>
<P>
China is using a new method of sending people abroad to study
this year, the official noted. Applications for study abroad are
reviewed by a group of experts from NSCIS, and the applicant must
sign a contract with NSCIS, he explained.
</P>
<P>
According to the contract, the person must pay an amount, not
to exceed 50,000 yuan (about 6,000 US dollars), in earnest money
to NSCIS, who will deposit the money in a designated bank.
</P>
<P>
The deposit and the interest will then be refunded to the
person if he or she returns within the specified amount of time
and does some service to the country. If not, the person will have
to pay the government for the study and will be fined for breaking
the contract.
</P>
<P>
The new method has been successfully tried out in Liaoning and
Hebei provinces, where 90 percent of their students studying
abroad returned on time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
