<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia To Develop Minerals And Energy Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A surge in mineral and energy
resource development put Australia in a position to take advantage
of commercial and development opportunities in the Asia-Pacific
region.
</P>
<P>
delivering the Julius Kruttschnitt Lecture in Brisbane, Federal
Resources and Energy Minister Warwick Parer said that billions of
dollars were being spent on existing and new projects across a
broad spectrum of the minerals and energy industry.
</P>
<P>
"I see a decade of impressive growth for the industries," the
minister was quoted by Australian Associated Press as saying this
evening.
</P>
<P>
The coal industry in New South Wales and Queensland had
committed one billion Australian dollars (about 740 million U.S.
dollars) to new projects, the petroleum industry had nearly two
billion dollars (1.48 billion U.S. dollars) in firm projects and
was looking at further projects valued at 30 billion dollars(22.2
billion U.S. dollars), while the copper and iron and steel
industries were spending more than two billion dollars each.
</P>
<P>
"The Australian Bureau of Agricultural and Resource Economics
has identified 70 other projects in various stages of planning,
which, if they go ahead, will involve more that 52 billion dollars
(38.5 billion U.S. dollars) in capital spending."
</P>
<P>
"We have aluminum smelters in Queensland and New South Wales
being expanded and major alumina capacity being added or
considered," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There are major works underway in Western Australia to process
iron ore, including BHP's hot briquetted iron plant, and others in
the pipeline which will see much more value added to our iron
resources."
</P>
<P>
Parer said the government believed Australia had a world
responsibility to develop and supply its mineral and energy
resources efficiently and with as little environmental impact as
possible.
</P>
<P>
"We are stewards of great natural wealth and as such we have a
responsibility to make it available to other nations in a
competitive marketplace and with minimal environmental effect," he
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
