<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gulf Arab States' Oil Income Expected to Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Gulf Arab states are likely to
earn less from oil exports in 1997 because of expected lower crude
prices, an expert here said today.
</P>
<P>
Ali Akber, an oil marketing manager in Abu Dhabi National Oil
Company (ADNOC), said, "I am not optimistic about reports that the
average oil price in the world could reach 18 U.S. dollars a
barrel this year."
</P>
<P>
"I expect prices to be lower than that level because of
several factors. They include Iraq's return to the market,
slackening demand in the third quarter, and excess output by some
oil producers," he said.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the price of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries' (OPEC) basket of seven crudes has averaged
about 19 dollars, higher than the average recorded in the same
period of 1996 but lower by nearly one dollar than the price for
the whole of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Oil experts in ADNOC said they expected prices to range
between 17 and 18 dollars in 1997 as they will likely slip in the
third quarter but pick up in the following three months when
demand recovers in the northern hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
At such a price range, the six Gulf Arab countries would earn
between 71 billion dollars and 75 billion dollars compared with a
13-year high of nearly 83 billion in 1996, when the average price
was as strong as 20.5 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf Arab states which include the United Arab Emirates,
Saudi Arabia, Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman and Qatar produce around 13.5
million barrels per day (bpd) of crude, of which nearly 11.5
million bpd are exported.
</P>
<P>
The output of the six states, four of which are OPEC members,
has remained almost unchanged over the past three years as they
countinued to stick to their shares in fear of a price collapse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
