<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thompson Wins Third Gold in Pan Pacific Swimming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- American Jenny Thompson snatched
her third gold medal at the Pan Pacific swimming championships in
Fukuoka, Japan, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old swimmer, who on Monday added a relay title to
her 100 meters freestyle gold, clocked a new meet record of 59.00
seconds to take the 100 meters butterfly final.
</P>
<P>
Thompson's time was also the best of the season in the world,
beating by 0.09 seconds the previous best set by Japanese Ayari
Aoyama at the East Asian Games in June in Pusan, South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Aoyama came second in 59.35, followed by Cai Huijue of China in
59.64.
</P>
<P>
Australian Grant Hackett shone in the men's 400 meters
freestyle with a winning time of 3:47.27 which was also a new
championship record.
</P>
<P>
Hackett's teammate Ian Thorpe came second in 3:49.64 with
American Chad Carvin third in 3:50.40.
</P>
<P>
The men's 100 meters butterfly final also produced a new meet
record as American Neil Walker touched home first in 52.76.
</P>
<P>
Australian Michael Klim finished second in 52.94 and American
Nathaniel Dusing was third in 53.26
</P>
<P>
American Lenny Krayzelburg got the men's 200 meters backstroke
title as he clocked a meet record of 1:57.87.
</P>
<P>
Claudia Poll of Costa Rica triumphed in the women's 400 meters
freestyle event by clocking 4:06.56 and Japanese Mai Nakamura
timed 2:11.40 to win the women's 200 meters backstroke final.
</P>
<P>
The United States now topped the medal standings with 13 golds,
four more than Australia. Host Japan and Costa Rica have won two
gold medals apiece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
