<HEADLINE> Pakistan Prepares Five-Year Plan to Combat TB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government is
preparing a comprehensive five-year plan involving 1.1 billion
rupees (about 30 million U.S. dollars) to combat increasing
incidence of tuberculoses (TB) in the country.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Federal Minister for Health Makhdoom
Javed Hashmi here today when talking to the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
An amount of 260 million rupees (about 6 million U.S. dollars)
will be spent this year against the disease, Hashmi said.
</P>
<P>
He said the World Bank has also promised to extend financial
help in the fight against TB.
</P>
<P>
The health minister admitted that the lethal disease was once
again getting roots in Pakistan and it was a very serious matter
that 500,000 cases of TB have been traced out in the country.
</P>
