<HEADLINE> Ramos Optimistic on Peace Talks with NDF Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today said the government and the National Democratic Front (NDF)
rebels have initialed three out of four substantive issues, paving
the way for a peace agreement between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said this was the latest report he received from the
government's chief negotiator Howard Dee, who was in the
Netherlands holding peace talks with the rebel group.
</P>
<P>
The president described the achievement as "a big step" toward
a peace agreement. However, he added that the three issues were
still subject to refinement.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks with the NDF constituted one of the two
remaining problems the government is wrapping up to restore total
peace and stability in the country.
</P>
<P>
The other one was the ongoing negotiations with the Moro
Islamic Liberation Front, a breakaway group of the mainstream Moro
National Liberation Front (MNLF).
</P>
<P>
The government signed a peace agreement with the MNLF last
September, putting an end to a 24-year-old civil war in the
southern Philippines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
