<HEADLINE> 11 People Killed in Flood in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Eleven people were killed
in flood caused by heavy rains in eastern Turkey, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted officials, who declined to be named, as
saying that eastern province of Agri suffered most in the
torrential rains, and the flood damaged 64 houses and killed 750
animals in Dogubayazit town of the province alone.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local newspaper Daily News reported today that
torrential rains flooded Monday at least 80 homes and offices in
low-lying areas of Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey, and
disrupted morning rush-hour traffic.
</P>
<P>
An Egyptian Airlines Boeing 767-300 jetliner on a flight from
Cairo to Istanbul skidded off the runway of the Istanbul Ataturk
Airport in the same day as it was landing, and got stuck in mud,
said the paper.
</P>
<P>
It said that the jetliner's brakes failed to hold in the
slippery conditions due to the heavy rain. None of the 136
passengers and 14 crew on board was hurt, it added. 
</P>
