<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN's Principle of Maintaining Consensus Faces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Foreign Minister
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said today that maintaining the principle of
consensus would be among ASEAN's major challenges in the future.
</P>
<P>
The test against the principle of consensus would be more
evident as ASEAN countries compete to safeguard their respective
interests especially in the economic field, he said on Malaysia's
TV1 this evening.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the different levels of economic progress among
ASEAN members might also pose problem in decision making.
</P>
<P>
However, he said ASEAN is a pragmatic organization capable of
finding solution to overcome the problem by extending assistance
to member countries concerned, taking into consideration their
development need.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations), which
celebrated its 30th anniversary on August 8, now has nine members
-- Malaysia, Singapore, Thailand, the Philippines, Indonesia,
Brunei, Vietnam, Laos and Myanmar, with the first five as founding
members.
</P>
<P>
The founding members together with Brunei which joined the
grouping in 1984 are economically strong while the last three,
particularly Laos and Myanmar which came into the ASEAN fold
simultaneously last month, are comparatively poorer.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah expressed the hope that ASEAN will continue to be a
relevant organization in the Southeast Asian region and continue
to progress in all fields and become more influential in the
future.
</P>
<P>
On what would bind ASEAN together in the future, Abdullah said
ASEAN would continue to be united based on the appreciation of the
principle of consensus which would see the grouping fostering
greater cooperation for the good of all.
</P>
<P>
He said one reason why ASEAN would emerge as one of the
successful organizations would be the freedom among member
countries to pursue agenda for their respective progress in spite
of the consensus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
