<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Customs Seize Record Batch of Cocaine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Customs officers
seized 10.4 kg of suspected cocaine at Kai Tak Airport, an
ever-largest single seizure of the drug this year, a spokesman of
the Customs said here today.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the seized drug from an incoming
passenger, a 40-year-old Brazilian man, is worth about 11.4
million HK dollars (1.47 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Shortly before 10 p.m. yesterday, the suspect was intercepted
for baggage examination by Airport Customs Officers when he
arrived from Bolivia via Brazil transiting Tokyo. Customs
officers found the suspected cocaine concealed inside two
Electronic Modular Switching Systems inside the suspect's
suitcase.
</P>
<P>
The cocaine is believed to be for consumption in local market,
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Since January 1997, the Customs and Excise Department has
seized a total of 30.1 kg of cocaine. The Customs seized 4.7 kg
of the drug in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that drug traffickers tend to smuggle
cocaine into Hong Kong by diversionary routing in order to divert
Customs attention.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Hong Kong Customs will continue to strengthen its
intelligence network and will closely monitor any emerging trend
in combating drug trafficking activities." 
</P>
</TEXT>
