<HEADLINE> Better Hong Kong Foundation Donates to Police Education Trusts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Better Hong Kong
Foundation today donated one million HK dollars (128,000 U.S.
dollars) to the Police Children's Education Trust and the Police
Education and Welfare Trust.
</P>
<P>
Police Commissioner Eddie Hui accepted the donation on behalf
of the trusts at a check presentation ceremony and said he is glad
that the community is in support of the police force.
</P>
<P>
The donation is a boost to the police's morale, he said.
</P>
<P>
The police force is a key element in maintaining the rule of
law, which is essential to HK's continuing success as an
international trading and financial center, according to the
foundation, which paid tribute to the dedication of Hong Kong's
more than 27,000 police officers.
</P>
<P>
Robert Ng, trustee of the foundation, said that Hong Kong's
streets are among the safest in the world and that the city's
crime rate is low by international standards.
</P>
<P>
He also spoke of the effective role played by the police force
during the handover, in ensuring this historic transition passed
off without incident.
</P>
<P>
The two police trusts provide bursars for secondary and
tertiary education, and special assistance for the disabled and
special needs, for the children of police officers.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, the trusts have granted bursars to
the amount of 27.2 million HK dollars (3.5 million U.S. dollars)
to 9,129 children of police officers.
</P>
<P>
The trusts were set up in the 1960s, and every effort has been
made to preserve capital so that the various bursars and other
benefits could be met from interest income.  
</P>
</TEXT>
