<HEADLINE> S. Africa's ANC Expects to Remove White Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's ruling
African National Congress (ANC) is planning to push for the total
removal of white dominance in all spheres of power, including the
economy, civil service, security forces and media control.
</P>
<P>
In a draft strategy released Monday, ANC spelt out its steps
toward what it called "total transformation" for debate among its
members ahead of its 50th national conference to be held in
December.
</P>
<P>
Presented to the media by ANC strategist and Transport
Minister Mac Maharaj, the document alludes to the notion that the
compromise political settlement in South Africa "presented
opportunities for those fundamentally opposed to change to
mobilize against it".
</P>
<P>
Total transformation, Maharaj said, means being vigilant
against active counter-revolutionary forces in his country.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past years in government, we have learned that we
should not be blinded by the fact that blacks are for the first
time occupying the highest political offices in the land. The
reality is that colonial relations in some centers of power
remain largely unchanged."
</P>
<P>
On privatization of state assets, Maharaj said the ANC's
vision of an inclusive democracy means it sees the rate and
direction of the privatization being dictated by the needs of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Maharaj also emphasised that the ANC remained in partnership
with the business circle and the labor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
