<HEADLINE> SADC States Urged to Explain Low Wages in Textile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Employers and governments
throughout the Southern African Development Community (SADC) has
been urged to explain massive wage discrepancies and conditions
of employment in the region, local press said today.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made yesterday in Durban by Jacu Ncgobo,
general secretary of the South African Clothing and Textile
Workers' Union (SACTWU).
</P>
<P>
"We believe a lot of money within the clothing and textile
industries, which should be going to the workers, is going to
governments in the form of high taxes," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
Ncgobo told the press that the employers and governments in
SADC region did not fully appreciate the implications of a
southern African trade bloc.
</P>
<P>
African governments would no longer be able to sanction low
wage levels and mass dismissals in the wake of strikes, as had
recently been the case in Zimbabwe, he said.
</P>
<P>
The SACTWU would stand by its recent decision to keep a
careful eye on labor and social clauses within the emerging
regional protocol, and push its demand that labor be included in
negotiations that would ultimately determine the overall trade
agreement, the union leader said.
</P>
<P>
Ncgobo said despite its concerns, the union was in favor of
the SADC trade bloc, especially now that Zambia demanded a
preferential trade agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
