<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Free Local Sugar Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is planning to float
domestic sugar prices next year, six years before the schedule of
2004 asked by World Trade Organization (WTO), a senior Thai
official said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, Thailand will open its market for sugar imports
while eliminating domestic and export quota system, according to
Pramote Vidtayasuk, secretary-general of the Cane and Sugar Board.
</P>
<P>
The planned liberalization of sugar imports is expected to
benefit local customers if the baht, which has devalued
significantly since July 2, strengthens, Pramote was quoted as
saying by local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The board on Monday froze domestic prices of raw sugar and
refined sugar at 12 baht and 13 baht (0.4 and 0.43 U.S. dollars)
per kilogram respectively until the end of this year. It is using
a cane and sugar fund to sustain local prices at a low level.
</P>
<P>
Thailand produces about 5.8 million tons of sugar a year, more
than half of which is for export. The country currently is one of
the leading sugar exporters in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
