<HEADLINE> German Inflation Surges to 13-Month High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 12 (Xinhua) -- German inflation rose to an
annualized rate of 1.9 percent in July, the highest rate recorded
since June 1996, the German federal statistics office said today.
</P>
<P>
The Wiesbaden-based office said that the month-on-month rise in
the latest price index was 0.5 percent in July, the highest single
month increase since January this year.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures reinforced the warning issued by the German
central bank last week that the price trends were moving "in the
wrong direction."
</P>
<P>
Germany's inflation rates were 1.6 percent and 1.7 percent in
May and June respectively. 
</P>
