<HEADLINE> German Central Bank Leaves Repurchase Rate Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The German central bank decided
today to leave its securities repurchase rate unchanged, ending
market speculations that the rate would be raised to check the
mark's steady decline against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The repurchase rate, applying to short-term liquidity provided
to banks which sell securities and then repurchase them at an
appointed date, has been frozen at 3.0 percent since August 1996.
</P>
<P>
Speculations about a rate hike came on July 24 when the German
central bank, Bundesbank, indicated that it would fix the
repurchase rate for just two weeks and then reassess its policy
according to developments on the markets.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the Bundesbank's latest decision to leave the
rate intact would provide an incentive for the dollar to
strengthen again after suffering slight losses against the mark
late last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Farmers Encouraged to Use Biopesticides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government urged
researchers to actively promote the use of biopesticide and
pesticides produced from plants to compete with chemical
pesticide.
</P>
<P>
"The use of biopesticide for plants has attracted more people
in the world and they tend to avoid chemical pesticide,"
Population and Environment Minister Sarwono Kusumaatmadja said
Monday in Surabaya, east Java, reports reaching here today said.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted as saying: "the most important thing now is to
encourage farmers to leave chemical pesticide so Indonesian
agriculture products will still be attractive in the international
market."
</P>
<P>
"Besides, the use of chemical pesticide in Indonesia has
already reached its saturation point, causing degradation of land
quality and affecting crop production," the minister said at a
two-day national conference (from August 11 to 12) aiming at
encouraging the use of biopesticide.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted, the government cannot ban all chemical
pesticides which are accused to be unfriendly to the environment
because the development of biopesticide is still in its premature
stage.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
