<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Get World Bank Loan for Energy Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank will continue to
provide the 125-million-US-Dollar loan to kenya for the
restructuring of the energy sector, according to a "Daily Nation"
report today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the Permanent Secretary of the Energy
Ministry, Crispus Mutitu as saying that the loan had not been
affected by the recent decision of the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) to suspend aid to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
After a high-level meeting with World Bank officials who were
in the country last week to review progress in the energy sector,
he noted that the government was currently involved in discussion
with the bank on future projects based on the reforms already
undertaken in the sector.
</P>
<P>
Mutitu said that the loan would be used to expand the power
system and upgrade the geothermal resources in the east African
country.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the energy sector had been the center of
debates in donor circles with some blaming the government for not
putting in place its commitment to privatization in the energy
sector.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Energy Minister Kirugi M'Mukinha was quoted as saying
last week that the Electricity Power Bill (1997) would soon be
tabled in Parliament this month.
</P>
<P>
The Bill, among other things, is expected to set the stage for
the privatization process in the energy sector, according to the
minister.
</P>
<P>
However, "Daily Nation" quoted the British paper "Financial
Times" as saying Friday that World Bank's support for Kenya could
also be "substantially reduced" unless Nairobi takes substantive
efforts to tackle the issue of corruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
