<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 41 Thai Firms Allowed to Resume Securities Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand has agreed
to allow 41 of the 58 suspended finance and securities firms to
resume their securities business, but under strict conditions, a
local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The 41 firms can deal with institutional investors and in cash
only, while brokerages and sub-brokerages must post bank
guarantees equal to the amount of money they invested in
securities, the Bangkok Post said.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after executives of the 41 firms Monday
met with officials of the central bank, the Securities and
Exchange Commission (SEC) and the Stock Exchange of Thailand, who
reiterated their call for the firms to separate their finance
business from securities business.
</P>
<P>
The requirement for bank guarantees is aimed at protecting
investors against risks in the securities business.
</P>
<P>
However, some executives of the firms complained that the term
"institutional investors" are not clear enough and the decision
was not fair for sub-brokerages or brokerages with retail clients.
</P>
<P>
The authorities concerned earlier had repeatedly urged finance
firms to separate their finance business from securities business,
warning them not to use depositors' money to invest in the
securities business. But the warning was widely ignored by finance
firms.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the SEC also agreed that it will waive a rule
requiring a finance firm to hold up to 99.99 percent of its
separated securities firm for six months after the separation, but
insisting that the foreign shareholding ceiling will remain at 49
percent for securities firms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
