<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Holy Place of Buddhist Sect Found in Shanxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A research team has learned that
a well-known Chinese Buddhist leader taught his disciples at the
foot of a mountain in north China's Shanxi Province, resolving the
long and heated dispute over where he preached.
</P>
<P>
The location of the grave of Master Tanluan, the founder of the
Jingtu Denomination of Chinese Buddhism, and the exact site of his
sermons, has been debated by Buddhists throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
After a period of strenuous work, Chinese archaeologists from
the Shanxi Institute of Buddhist Culture finally determined the
precise spot.
</P>
<P>
Master Tanluan, also a famous philosopher, propagated the
Buddhist principles during the Northern and Southern Dynasties of
about 1,500 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The place where he delivered his teachings is called the Rock
of Luangong and is regarded as holy by his followers. In its
halcyon days it attracted many visitors, but later became
forgotten as limited transportation routes kept sightseers away.
</P>
<P>
The Rock of Luangong is in Mianshan Mountain between Jiexiu and
Lingshi counties in Shanxi Province. The temple and relics in the
hidden cave were destroyed by Japanese invaders during the War of
Resistance Against Japan from 1937 to 1945.
</P>
<P>
In 1920, an eminent Japanese monk found the Xuanzhong Temple,
the origin of the Jingtu Buddhist Sect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Reports Ozone Depletion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Belgian meteorologists reported
a low concentration of ozone for the fifth time this year.
</P>
<P>
The Free Belgium newspaper said today that readings in three of
the country's 22 measuring stations showed ozone concentration at
between 186 micrograms and 217 micrograms per cubic meter of air,
well below the 360 micrograms set as a benchmark for alarms.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper, however, quoted meteorologist Alain Derouane as
saying that authorities were publishing ozone readings only as a
piece of information and not as a warning.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has instructed its member states to inform
their populace whenever ozone depletion occurs.
</P>
<P>
The four previous readings of low concentration of ozone this
year were taken last weekend and on June 4 and July 12.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists explained that the frequency of ozone depletion
in the country has been on the decline as against that posted a
couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
As many as 32 below-360 micrograms concentration were reported
in 1995 and 20 registered in 1994. Meteorologists estimated that
1984 had some 30 ozone depletion occurences.
</P>
<P>
The ozone layer of the atmosphere absorbs solar ultraviolet
radiation, protecting lives on the earth from harmful solar
radiation of wavelengths less than 290 nanometers.
</P>
<P>
Waste gases like automobile exhausts bear the brunt of blame
and criticism for ozone depletion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Opposes Total Ban on Anti-Personnel Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 12 (Xinhua) -- South Korea opposes a total ban on
anti-personnel mines, given the security situation on the Korean
peninsula, a ministry official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, however, may agree to a ban on the transfer of
anti-personnel landmines, Yonhap News Agency quoted the official
on anonymity as saying.
</P>
<P>
South Korea joined the 1995 Moratorium banning the transfer of
anti-personnel landmines and stated it will support the extension
of the moratorium, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of total ban of anti-personnel landmines, the
official said his government will persist its reservation, adding
that the U.S. government will also likely not change its position
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
When they met last month in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia,
U.S. Secretary of State Medeleine Albright and her South Korean
counterpart Yoo Chong-ha agreed that use of the landmines on the
Korean peninsula was inevitable under the special security
situation.
</P>
<P>
The official said that his government will not oppose
discussions on a ban on anti-personnel landmines at the Conference
on Disarmament, however, South Korea will not joint the so-called
Ottawa Process which has been pursuing a total ban on the
production, development, use and transfer of anti-personnel
landmines under no exceptions.
</P>
<P>
In a worst case scenario in which the United States joins the
Ottawa Process, only those landmines planted by the U.S. in
Demilitarized Zones will be affected, according to another
South Korean official.
</P>
<P>
"Realistically speaking, the removal of all landmines already
planted will prove difficult from a view of technical point,
although it is mandated under the agreement to be signed, " he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Hold Next Round of Talks with Tribal Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government and
southeastern tribal rebels are expected to held another round of
talks in Dhaka next month, in a bid to reach an agreement for a
durable peace in the troubled Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT), said
informed sources.
</P>
<P>
The talks will be the sixth round of dialogue between the two
sides to hammer out a formula for resolving the two decade-old
problem in the three pro-independence hill districts.
</P>
<P>
Chief Whip Abdullah will lead the government side while the
tribal delegation to the talks will be headed by Shantu Larma,
head of the Parbatya Chattagram Jana Sanghati Samity (PCJSS),
political wing of the armed Chakma rebels.
</P>
<P>
The last round of talks, also held in Dhaka in July, continued
for five days, but without reaching any final accord.
</P>
<P>
Total repatriation of the Bangladeshi Chakma refugees, now
languishing in camps in the Indian state of Tripura, is one of the
major threats to peace and stability in the three resource-rich
hill districts.
</P>
<P>
The situation worsened following an inconclusive talks a few
days ago between Dhaka and the Chakma tribal refugee leaders in
Tripura.
</P>
<P>
The talks held early this month bogged down after 10 hours of
marathon deliberations as some fresh demands were put forward by
the tribal delegation, said a member of the government delegation.
</P>
<P>
The demands include involvement of international agencies in
the repatriation process, providing financial assistance to all
returnees, including those who returned in 1994, increase of cash
and food ration from nine months to one year and rehabilitation of
all displaced persons in the hill tracts.
</P>
<P>
The government considers all these demands "unwanted and
unfortunate" at the present stage, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, some 6,000 refugees were repatriated
following an agreement was reached between Dhaka and the Chakma
refugees. The second phase of repatriation, however, was halted as
the refugees claimed that the government had not fully complied
with its commitments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
