<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Tops Uganda's Trade List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Kenya maintained Uganda's major
trade partner position last year, supplying Uganda with 34
percent of its imports, reported "The Monitor" daily today.
</P>
<P>
According to provisional statistics just released by the
Ministry of Planning, Uganda imported goods worth 729 million
U.S. Dollars in total in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Kenya was followed by Britain, from which Uganda imported
goods worth 103 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Although Uganda is steadily industrializing and blocking
imports from its neighbors, it is still dependent on Kenya for
many of its industrial imports.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's Mombasa Port is also Uganda's main link to the sea.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Uganda's imports from Tanzania were worth 15.5
million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Business analysts said Uganda's trade with its southern
neighbor Tanzania could be boosted by joint railway and road
projects being undertaken by the two countries, and also by the
strengthening of the East African Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe exported to Uganda goods worth 2.3 million Dollars
last year.
</P>
<P>
No other African countries are mentioned in the report.
However, it is believed that imports from South Africa, the
continent's economic giant, were on the rise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
