<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Illiteracy Rate Alarming, UNDP Warns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) has warned Nigeria of its alarming illiteracy
rate, put at 46 percent of the total population, the Punch paper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Illiteracy remains a very serious problem with Nigeria, the
UNDP said in a recent report on the country, adding that only
about 62.5 percent of its male population and 39.5 percent of the
female population are literate.
</P>
<P>
The organization called for a massive and effective adult
literacy campaign in Nigeria, warning that otherwise the
situation will go beyond reasonable level.
</P>
<P>
It urged the government and the people of Nigeria to pursue
the objective of "education for all" within the next decade with
a single-minded determination.
</P>
<P>
In a country where a universal primary education was
introduced in some regions as early as 1950s and adopted at
national level over 20 years ago, there is no falling back in the
realization of this goal, the UNDP said.
</P>
<P>
It estimated that in 1994, out of a total population of 45
school-age children, only 50.4 percent were receiving education.
</P>
