<HEADLINE> Nigerians Urged to Help Renovate Primary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Nigerians have been urged to make
contribution to the rehabilitation of the country's primary
schools, which requires nearly one billion U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The government alone could not handle or provide the money and
would require communities, parents-teachers associations and
philanthropists to assist, a top official of National Primary
Education Commission said on Monday (NPEC).
</P>
<P>
According to NPEC Executive Secretary Ali Adamu, two thirds
out of 42,000 primary schools in the country require major
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
He said his commission also needs money to buy motor vehicles
for inspection of schools and distribution of teaching materials,
including motorcycles and boats for use in rural and riverine
areas.
</P>
<P>
Other classroom accommodations will also be bought, he said,
adding that furniture worth 170 million Naira (about two million
Dollars) will be purchased this year alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
