<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., China Share Strategic Interests, Carter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. President Jimmer
Carter has urged the United States to pursue ways to co-exist
peacefully and productively with China for the sake of mutual
strategic interests.
</P>
<P>
In a signed article carried by The New York Times Sunday,
Carter said that China and the United States continue to share
many interests: maintaining peace and stability in the
Asia-Pacific region, controlling weapons of mass destruction,
resolving the Korean peninsula issue.
</P>
<P>
He warned that ill-informed commentators and the forecast of
inevitable confrontation would put the accomplishments of a
quarter century at risk.
</P>
<P>
Carter echoed James Sasser, U.S. ambassador to China, who
expressed the hope that the planned summit between Chinese
President Jiang Zemin and U.S. President Bill Clinton "will
establish a strategic framework."
</P>
<P>
In an interview published by the "Newsweek International" in
its latest issue, Sasser said that the summit "will establish a
strategic framework wherein the United States and China can relate
to each other in the coming years."
</P>
<P>
The former senator cites numerous areas of joint strategic
interest including maintaining peace and security in Asia, dealing
with the proliferation of both nuclear and non-nuclear weapons,
terrorism, international drug trafficking, trade issues and
environmental cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
