<HEADLINE> Israeli High Tech Exports to Double by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Israeli high tech exports
will double from current 7 billion U.S. dollars a year to 14
billion dollars a year by 2000, The Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published by the daily newspaper, Israeli
chief scientist Orna Berry was quoted as saying Israeli high tech
sector is currently growing by 30 percent a year. High tech
companies are also improving their marketing strategies, which
should help boost exports.
</P>
<P>
Berry said she is now offering investment aid to
non-traditional high-tech companies in order to support companies
that will increase value-added margins by making manufacturing
processes more efficient.
</P>
<P>
She has recently returned from a trip to the U.S., where
she met with representatives from investment banks, including
Salomon Brothers, Price Waterhouse and Robertson &AMP; Stevens, in
an effort to encourage them to invest in Israel's biotechnology
companies.
</P>
<P>
She also met with David Schick, CEO of Schick Technologies, a
New York-based manufacturer of digital radiographic imaging
systems that is currently in talks to purchase an undisclosed
Israeli company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
