<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Regional Courts Demand for More Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's regional
courts and magistrates have urged the government to authorize
them more power to enable them to impose heavier sentences for
serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
Les Wilkens, chairman of the Association of Regional courts
and Magistrates of South Africa said on Monday that regional
courts wanted alterations made to the law which only allows them
power to impose sentences of up to 10 years imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
"This maximum is clearly insufficient with most of the serious
crimes such as murder, rape, bank robbery and vehicles hijacking
being tried in the regional courts," Wilkens told the Portfolio
Committee on Justice's public hearings on the criminal law
amendment bill.
</P>
<P>
The amended bill proposes that trial courts impose another
sentence to replace the death sentence to amend laws relating to
the death penalty and to provide minimum sentences for certain
serious offenses.
</P>
<P>
Wilkens said his organization was also calling for gender
equalization in cases of indecent assault. He said the same age
that applied for girls in cases of indecent assault should also
apply to boys at present. It is 14 for a boy and 12 for a girl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
