<HEADLINE> Qatar to Regulate Financial Investment Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Qatar is to issue a law
regulating activities of investment companies in the Gulf state
within weeks, Qatar Central Bank has announced.
</P>
<P>
"We are outlining regulations for investment firms and will be
issuing them within weeks," Khaleej Times today quoted Abdullah
bin Khaled, governor of Qatar Central Bank as saying.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations, intended to bolster the state's growing
financial markets, would shift the regulatory authority over
locally incorporated investment companies from the Ministry of
Finance, Economy and Trade to the central bank, the governor
said in an interview with the newspaper on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said the new law would set a minimum capital requirement
for locally-registered investment firms, which invest mainly on
international markets, the newspaper said. Further details were
not yet given.
</P>
<P>
Under the present system, investment firms registered with the
Ministry of Finance, Economy and Trade are not required to
maintain a minimum capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
