<HEADLINE> Sacked NZ Minister to Stay with Own Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Sacked associate health
minister of New Zealand Neil Kirton said today he will stay with
his New Zealand First party.
</P>
<P>
Kirton announced his decision after meeting the caucus of New
Zealand First, report TVNZ tonight.
</P>
<P>
He said he will remain in the party to fight for NZ First's
principles.
</P>
<P>
Kirton was sacked by his party chief Winston Peters for
disobeying Peters' order not to talk to the media about his
disagreement with Health Minister Bill English, who is from NZ
First's coalition partner, the National Party.
</P>
<P>
But both Kirton and Peters today dismissed last week's event as
a misunderstanding and said they had decided to put it behind.
</P>
<P>
Kirton pledged his loyalty to New Zealand First and his
commitment to the coalition government.
</P>
<P>
He had said after being fired that he would consider all
options for his future. His decision today has cleared the
uncertainty surrounding the coalition, which enjoys a one-seat
majority in the 120-member parliament.  
