<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 07:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Envoy Criticizes Israeli Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Mideast peace envoy
Dennis Ross has criticized Israeli measures taken against the
Palestinians following last month's suicide bombings in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Ross made the criticism after holding a third meeting in
Ramallah Monday night with Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
leader Yasser Arafat. He described some Israeli measures as
"counterproductive toward its security and the peace process."
</P>
<P>
This was Ross's first criticism against Israel. It seemed to
be a balance act to console the Palestinian side, which
complained that Ross should not focus his attention only on the
security matters in favor of Israel while neglecting the
suffering of the Palestinian people under Israeli sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Ross reiterated that the objective of
his trip is to help resume the Israeli-Palestinian security
cooperation. He urged Israelis and Palestinians to work as
partners to fight the common threat of militant extremism.
</P>
<P>
He reported some progress in his first two day mediation,
saying that Israel and the PNA had come a step closer to revive
the security cooperation. But he added that the success should
be measured by results.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian intelligence chief Amin Hindi held a second
meeting with Israeli General Security Service head Ami Ayalon
and Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's attorney Yitzhak
Molcho Monday night following their first meeting Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
The two meetings were attended by U.S. officials from
the Central Intelligence Agency.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, Ross held a series of talks with Israeli
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, Foreign Minister David Levy,
European Union peace envoy Miguel Moratinos and Egypt's
Ambassador to Israel Mohammed Bassiouny.
</P>
<P>
He was trying to mobilize all the peace forces in a bid to
resume the stalled Israeli-Palestinian security cooperation to
pave the way for resuming the political negotiations. He is
scheduled to hold the third meeting today with Netanyahu to
explore ways of breaking the ice.
</P>
<P>
Following the July 30 twin suicide bombings in Jerusalem's
Mahane Yehuda market which killed 15 people and wounded 170
others, Israel immediately imposed a total closure on
Palestinian territories, canceling the scheduled resumption of
peace talks, and halting transfer of tax revenues it collected
from the Palestinians on the PNA's behalf.
</P>
<P>
Israel conditions the resumption of peace process on the PNA's
promise to launch a long-term crackdown on Islamic militant
organizations, but the PNA insists that Israel should first lift
all its sanctions against the Palestinian people before resuming
bilateral security cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
