<HEADLINE> Religious Leaders to Mediate in Reform Talks in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Religious leaders have
appointed a nine-man team to mediate the dialogue for
constitutional reforms between the ruling and opposition parties,
local paper "East African Standard" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Moslem and Christian leaders are scheduled to meet today
to name their chairman of the mediating team and expected to
issue a comprehensive statement over the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued here on Monday by the National Christian
Council of Kenya (NCCK) said that religious leaders appealed to
all Kenyans to avoid any activities which could lead to violence.
</P>
<P>
The National Convention Executive Council also issued a press
statement yesterday, saying that they were suspending any further
mass action to give dialogue a chance.
</P>
<P>
The NCCK noted that the meeting was held yesterday in response
to requests from the ruling Kenya African National Union (KANU),
opposition parties and civil society for religious leaders to
play a mediatory role in the reform talks.
</P>
<P>
Archbishop David Gitari announced on Sunday that the
government had mandated religious leaders to broker the reform
dialogue between the KANU and the Opposition.
</P>
<P>
Religious leaders have in the recent past met with President
Daniel arap Moi twice to seek commencement of the dialogue and
the formation of the mediating team appears to be the first
serious overtune in the quest for constitutional reforms in the
country. 
</P>
