<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Steady Growth Still Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Can the Southeast Asian economy
survive the current currency crisis and maintain its steady growth
this year?
</P>
<P>
Most economists and analysts have given a very positive answer,
despite the currency crisis which hit most Southeast Asian nations
recently.
</P>
<P>
The crisis, triggered by Thailand's decision to let its baht
float on July 2 and speculative attacks, has forced Thailand, the
Philippines, Indonesia, Malaysia and Singapore to devalue their
currencies during the past month.
</P>
<P>
At present, the foreign exchange markets have become relatively
quiet although some currencies, such as the Malaysian ringgit, are
still under pressure.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Malaysian ringgit was languishing at 2.7337 to
2.7347 to the U.S. dollar, the weakest in 42 months. Most foreign
exchange dealers expect further losses.
</P>
<P>
The crisis is not over yet, but Southeast Asia has already seen
interest rates high, price hikes, and new lay-off, which are
affecting the once fast-growing economies in the world.
</P>
<P>
Where are the "tiger economies" heading for in the second half
of the year?
</P>
<P>
Economists predicted that the fast-growing cycle is definitely
over, but the growth rate of 4 percent to 6 percent is still
possible for Southeast Asian nations, except Thailand.
</P>
<P>
In the Southeast Asian region, most countries are facing
similar problems with Thailand, such as non-performing loans,
large current account deficit, slower export growth and dependence
on easy foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
But analysts said that countries like the Philippines,
Indonesia, Singapore and Malaysia are unlikely to suffer a
Thai-style financial crisis because their economic fundamentals
remain "solid".
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, which was described as "the next Thailand"
by some economists, the government insisted that the 1997 economic
growth target of 7 percent can be achieved while inflation will
remain at single-digit level of between 6 percent to 6.5 percent
after the de facto devaluation of the peso.
</P>
<P>
The weak peso, which has depreciated from 26.5 pesos to the
U.S. dollar to around 28.5 against the dollar now since July 11,
could make the country's export products more competitive, the
government said.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of the year, the Philippines' exports
increased by 22.1 percent and the higher export growth prompted by
the peso devaluation will help the country achieve its objective,
the government said.
</P>
<P>
In Malaysia, signs of a drop in exports, slowing investment
inflows and worries that interest rates will remain high have
prompted economists to revise downwards their gross domestic
product (GDP) forecast for this year between 7 percent and 7.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
Morgan Stanley Asia Ltd. is by far the most pessimistic,
forecasting in a recent report that the country's GDP growth will
slow to 6.1 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Compared with that of Western countries, such a growth rate is
still very impressive. But the Malaysian economy had grown by over
8 percent over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's economic prospects could be even brighter,
according to some analysts.
</P>
<P>
Dennis de Tray, director of the World Bank in Indonesia, said:
"We are projecting continued strong economy. We're projecting
exports to expand back to the type of levels of 1995, up to levels
in the 10 percent to 13 percent range. We're projecting a current
account deficit of around 4 billion dollars for the forthcoming
year. We think growth will stay up around 7.75 percent."
</P>
<P>
The size of the domestic market alone will probably ensure that
Indonesia remains attractive to foreign investors, whatever shocks
lie ahead, he said.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, the government has revised its 1997 growth target
from 5 percent to 6-7 percent after the country registered a 5.9
percent increase for the economy in the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
Singapore has registered its best export performance since May
1996, raising confidence in the long-awaited rebound in economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's non-oil exports in nominal terms grew 8.8 percent
in June to 5.09 billion dollars compared with a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Rising global demand for electronic goods will drive
Singapore's non-oil exports in nominal terms up 12 percent to 18
percent in the second half of the year, economists said.
</P>
<P>
With the improvement of its export performance, the growth
target is attainable, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, the future of the Thai economy is hard to
predict. But as the International Monetary Fund and Asian nations
pledged 16 billion dollars of loans to Thailand Monday in Tokyo,
the Thai economic performance will be much better than expected,
economist said.
</P>
<P>
As the fundamentals for economic growth remain in place in
Southeast Asia nations after currency devaluation, steady increase
for their national economies are still expected.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dengue Fever Spreads in South Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Dengue fever, which is sweeping
Vietnam's southern Mekong Delta, has killed 90 people so far in
this rainy season, the English language newspaper Vietnam News
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Tra Vinh Province topped the list with 5,071 dengue cases and
43 dengue-related deaths, three times more than the same period
last year while Ca Mau Province reported 4,600 cases and 12
deaths.
</P>
<P>
Kien Giang Province announced 25 deaths out of 2,855 cases. Soc
Trang province had over 800 cases and four deaths. Can Tho
Province had 966 cases and six deaths caused by the disease.
</P>
<P>
Most of the patients were children.
</P>
<P>
Local hospitals and agencies have been mobilized to treat the
patients while distributing insecticides to kill mosquitos which
transmit the cholera-like disease, particularly during rainy
season.
</P>
<P>
Doctors are urging all residents in the southern region to use
mosquito nets to avoid contracting the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
