<HEADLINE> Resettlement to Be Accelerated in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe will accelerate
resettlement and rural development with 1,772 more farms
identified for redistribution, President Robert Mugabe has said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, 1.3 billion Zimbabwe Dollars (about 110 U.S.
Dollars) has also been allocated for rural and water development.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the crucial question of land reform and development
in his national address on Heroes Day in Harare yesterday,
President Mugabe vowed to press ahead with both.
</P>
<P>
He said those who fought for the liberation of Zimbabwe would
receive preference when it came to distributing farms taken over
under the Land Acquisition Act. The program of allocating land
for their resettlement will be an ongoing exercise.
</P>
<P>
When addressing an estimated 15,000 people gathered at the
National Heroes Acre to commemorate Heroes Day, Mugabe said the
government was mindful of the plight of ex-combatants and had
enacted the War Veterans' Act and decided to create the War
Veterans' fund to finance business projects which will
economically empower war veterans in agriculture and
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said there would also be a Rural Development Fund that
would be used specifically for the provision, among other
projects, of rural roads, bore-holes, sanitation facilities,
clinics and small to medium-sized dams in rural districts.
</P>
<P>
This new approach to rural development, he said, would result
in improved infrastructure in the rural areas with a significant
impact on the social lives of the rural people.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, a group of demonstrating ex-combatants
interrupted proceedings to commemorate Heroes Day at the National
Heroes Acre, claiming the government had failed to resolve their
problems.
</P>
<P>
The group of at least 100 men and women sang, shouted slogans
and played drums throughout the ceremony. Their noise rose during
the playing of Zimbabwe's national anthem and during the address
by President Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
Master of ceremonies and Minister of Defense Moven Mahachi
described the demonstration as disgraceful, wondering whether the
ex-combatants had genuine cases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
