<HEADLINE> Rare Species of Plants at Three Gorges Area Protected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 12 (Xinhua) -- More than 40 rare species of
plants in the Three Gorges area which have been re-planted
elsewhere are thriving, with over half of them now in bloom.
</P>
<P>
There are 3,964 species of seeded plants in the region,
accounting for a seventh of the national total. Some of the plants
will be affected by the damming of the Three Gorges, said Jin
Yixin, research fellow at the Wuhan Botanical Research Institute
under the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS).
</P>
<P>
Protection of rare species in the Three Gorges area attracted
worldwide attention immediately after the project was put on the
Chinese government's agenda.
</P>
<P>
Early in 1983, CAS organized a group of more than 2,000 experts
to study the project's influence on the ecosystem and to find
solutions to the problems that surfaced. The experts then decided
to move some 40 rare species out of the area.
</P>
<P>
Now, 80 percent of them are growing well in Yichang, Wuhan and
other places, Jin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
