<HEADLINE> Tombs of Ming Dynasty Unearthed in Liuzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A group of 11 tombs built during
the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644) have been unearthed in the city of
Liuzhou, southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists from the city museum collected what was left of
the cultural relics from eight of the tombs, which had been
damaged by construction workers. Excavation work is continuing on
the other three tombs.
</P>
<P>
Also found at the site were two well-preserved bodies covered
with bronze and silver decorative items, some blue and white pots
and bronze mirrors.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the discovery will benefit the study of social and
economic development and folk customs during the Ming dynasty.
 
</P>
