<HEADLINE> Southwest Chinese City Striving to Improve Investment Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The capital of Sichuan Province,
southwest China, has developed measures to improve its investment
environment to get more overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
He Shaohua, vice-mayor of Chengdu, said his city has set up a
center to provide overseas investors with investment and
management services and an overseas investor complaint center.
</P>
<P>
Illegal levies on foreign-funded enterprises have been
outlawed, he said, and the local government has set a single
standard for overseas investors showing what they should pay --
and what not.
</P>
<P>
The city government has also urged all of its departments to
improve their efficiency, and foreign investors can obtain a
license for their projects within 20 working days if they have
prepared all the essential documents.
</P>
<P>
The city has approved more than 2,000 foreign-funded projects
in the past few years, involving some 1.2 billion US dollars in
overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
Some multinationals have invested in the city, including
Germany's Siemens, the US's P&AMP;G and the Daewoo Corp. of the
Republic of Korea (ROK).  
</P>
</TEXT>
