<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Economy Picking Up in 2nd Quarter: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Growth momentum of the
Singapore economy picked up significantly in the second quarter
this year with the economy expanding by 7.8 percent on a
year-on-year basis, the Economic Survey of Singapore for the
second quarter, published today, said.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate recorded in the first quarter was only 4.1
percent, the survey noted.
</P>
<P>
It said that except for business services, all sectors
registered faster growth in the second quarter, with manufacturing
showing the most significant pick-up.
</P>
<P>
After three consecutive quarters of decline, the manufacturing
sector expanded by 3.2 percent in the second quarter, largely due
to a strong pick-up in June, as growth was driven by electronics,
transport equipment and chemicals.
</P>
<P>
Within the electronics sub-sector, higher export demand boosted
the output of disk drives and telecommunications equipment.
</P>
<P>
However, the survey found that the output in the consumer
electronics and printed circuit board assembly segments remained
relatively weak due to keen competition.
</P>
<P>
The financial and business services sector grew by 10.6
percent, little changed from a quarter ago, while the transport
and communications sector expanded by 9.5 percent, up from 8
percent recorded in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
A jump in entrepot trade growth to 15 percent in the second
quarter helped propel commerce sector growth to 7.9 percent, up
from 2.8 percent a quarter earlier. The construction industry
reported an 11.8 percent growth in the second quarter, up from the
ten percent in the previous three-month period.
</P>
<P>
The survey noted that the growth was largely supported by
public-sector building and upgrading activities and
infrastructural projects.
</P>
<P>
As for the prospects of economic growth in the second half of
the year, the survey said that domestically, forward-looking
indicators like the Composite Leading Index and business
expectations of the commerce and transport and storage sectors
have turned more favorable.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector is expected to continue to recover in
the second half, while the commerce sector and hub services are
also likely to benefit from the electronics recovery and stronger
trade growth, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Province Improving Structure of Private Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The number of private
businesses in east China's Zhejiang Province decreased by 100,000
during the first half of this year, whereas their total registered
capital went up by 7.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
This change is attributed to fierce market competition and the
growing presence of large-scale operations. The small-scale
cottage industries have been replaced by stock companies emerging
in the sector.
</P>
<P>
In the city of Ningbo, 17,000 private firms were closed due to
slack business, while others went bankrupt as a result of poor
management. In the second quarter of this year, the province saw a
drop in the number of private businesses.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of larger scale private enterprises is
going up steadily; businesses each with over five million yuan in
registered capital have increased by 12.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang has also established more than 30,000 private stock
companies as well as over 100 enterprise groups.
</P>
<P>
And the investment structure of the private sector is changing,
with more capital going to agriculture and the service
sector. During the first six months, private businesses in
agriculture registered a total capital of 420 million yuan, up
nearly 50 percent, while those in industry dropped by 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
More private businesses have begun to shift their investment
priority to technology-intensive projects. In Linghai, 36 key
private enterprises spent 26.52 million yuan on technological
improvement projects in the second quarter of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
