<HEADLINE> De Beers Seeks to Set up Full Subsidiary in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 12 (Xinhua) -- South African diamond mining
and marketing giant De Beers has applied to the Indian government
for permission to set up a 100 percent subsidiary in the country,
a government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The move came just a few years after the company was allowed to
set up a 50-50 joint venture with India's reliance industries for
prospecting and mining diamonds in Madhya Pradesh in central
India.
</P>
<P>
De Beers' application clearly indicated that it is not
depending exclusively on the joint venture for its entry into
India.
</P>
<P>
A senior De Beers executive said that "at the moment, we are
not sure what kind of entity, in terms of equity holding, the
government will approve of in diamond prospecting and mining. So
while we have already had a joint venture with an Indian partner,
we are also setting up a 100 percent subsidiary to make sure that
we can participate in the tender process in whatever form the
government decides."
</P>
<P>
"We are keen to take part in the bidding process for
prospecting and mining of diamonds. However we are waiting for the
government to come out with specific norms for the tender
process," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Madhya Pradesh government has set up a committee to suggest
a diamond prospecting and mining policy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
