<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Takes Steps Encouraging Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 12 (Xinhua) -- the Reserve Bank of India
(RBI) has allowed foreign institutional investors (FIIs) to buy
the forward cover for their investments in debt instruments as the
first concrete step towards capital account convertibility,
finance ministry sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Tarapore Committee, which had drawn up a blueprint for
capital account convertibility over three phases, had suggested
that all participants in the spot market such as FIIs,
non-residents and non-resident banks should be allowed to opt for
forward cover in the first phase.
</P>
<P>
The RBI reckons that it is now opportune to implement the first
phase of the plan as the forward cover rates have been weak. The
premia rates are expected to rise once FIIs start covering their
investments in debt instruments.
</P>
<P>
The authorized dealers could provide forward cover to FIIs in
respect of their investments in debt instruments. The extent of
the cover would be limited to the current market value of the
investments in debt instruments translated in U.S. dollar terms.
The tenure of the cover will not exceed the remaining period to
maturity. This suggests that the FIIs would have to have an
underlying investment in debt before booking the cover. On the
basis of this investment, the FIIs would be allowed to book the
forward contract to the extent of the current market value of its
debt investments translated in U.S. dollar terms.
</P>
<P>
The step has been welcomed by FIIs as well as foreign exchange
market players and observers as a positive signal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 89 People Arrested, Tons of Drugs Seized in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. police have arrested 89
people and seized tons of cocaine and marijuana and millions of
dollars in recent raids on drug runners from Mexico, police
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
In Monday's raids, police captured a total of 11.4 tons of
cocaine, 6.4 tons of marijuana and 18.5 million U.S. dollars in
cash. At least 28 people were arrested.
</P>
<P>
The attacks disclosed major new inroads by Mexicans into the
New York City market, said Thomas A. Constantine, administrator of
the Drug Enforcement Administration.
</P>
<P>
He estimated that the cocaine trafficked from Mexico account
for 30 percent to 35 percent of the total amount distributed in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Among the arrested were two alleged leaders of the Mexican drug
distribution operation in the New York City area. One of them,
Martin Manzo, was arrested Monday. The other, Alejandro Ortiz, was
arrested earlier, Constantine said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
