<HEADLINE> Foreign Trained Thai Doctors Granted Privilege </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will allow
Thai doctors who obtained their qualifications overseas to
practice in rural areas without applying for a certificate from
the Thai Medical Council, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made recently by the Thai Public Health
Ministry in a bid to ease the shortage of doctors in the country,
especially in remote areas.
</P>
<P>
Some 708 community hospitals around the country face a shortage
of about 2,500 doctors and 21 of these hospitals even do not have
a single doctor stationed there, officials from the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign trained Thai doctors may practice in community
hospitals for two years before they apply for a certificate, they
said.
</P>
<P>
This will enable them to familiarize themselves with Thai
medical practices and help them to obtain a Thai certificate, the
officials noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
