<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Exports Rise 23.4 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's export value posted
140.5 billion baht (4.68 U.S. dollars), up 26.7 billion baht (890
million dollars) or 23.4 percent compared with July last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics by the Thai Customs Department
available today, the figure is also up 16.6 percent over the
previous month.
</P>
<P>
The export jump in July this year was mainly attributed to the
depreciation of the baht, not to the improvement of the quality of
local products or exploration of new markets, the department said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the department also said that the country's import
value totaled 159.4 billion baht in July (5.31 billion dollars),
up 5.3 billion baht or 3.5 percent over July 1996 and 5.4 percent
over the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's total export value in the first seven months this
year recorded 867.2 billion baht, up 6.5 percent over the same
period of last year, while its import value totaled 1,100 billion
baht, also up 3.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The items enjoying the highest export values during the period
included electrical appliances and equipment, rubber and products,
seafood, pearls, diamonds, grains, garments and plastic goods.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Commerce Ministry has set an export target of 1.5
trillion baht for this year, up 10 percent over 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Labor Secretary Calls for Talks Between UPS, Teamsters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States Labor
Secretary Alexis Herman met with leaders of the United Parcel
Service (UPS) and the Teamsters Union to resume talks as the
strike by 185,000 Teamsters members entered its 8th day today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Herman said that during her separate meetings
with Teamsters and UPS leaders, she discussed in detail what it
would take to get them back to the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
"I made it clear that everyone involved must show greater
flexibility and a willingness to compromise," she said.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with Herman, Teamsters President Ron Carey
said he asked her to urge the company to bargain on the union's
key issues of full-time jobs, subcontracting and increased wages.
</P>
<P>
UPS' chief negotiator David Murray, emerging from a meeting
with Herman, said, "We still believe the correct solution to this
is for the Teamsters to put our people back to work."
</P>
<P>
UPS, meanwhile, sent a letter to members of Congress, intending
to pressure President Bill Clinton to intervene the strike.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Newt Gingrich responded quickly, urging Clinton
to help resolve the dispute. "I urge you to use every effort to
help resolve this dispute as quickly as possible," Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton has been insisting that the inconveniences of the
strike do not imperil the nation's health and safety -- the
standard for government intervention under the 1947 Taft-Hartley
Act.
</P>
<P>
On the labor side, AFL-CIO President John Sweeney called the
Teamsters strike "very effective" and promised financial or any
other kind of assistance the union wishes.
</P>
<P>
The two sides dispute over several issues, but focus on
two: the company's demand to withdraw from the Teamsters'
multi-employer pension plan and the union's call to convert
thousands of part-time jobs into full-time ones.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-eight percent of UPS employees work part time, and there
has been no increase in their base wage of eight dollars an
hour since 1982, much lower than the full-time employees.
</P>
<P>
UPS normally handles 12 million parcels and letters daily. The
work stoppage has damaged small businesses operations throughout
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
