<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Secures 16 Billion U.S. Dollar Aid from IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has secured at least 16
billion U.S. dollars in a rescue package for its volatile
financial system from the international community led by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF), according to reports reaching
here today.
</P>
<P>
The IMF and other Asian economies pledged to fulfill their
commitments to the aid package to help Thailand rebuild its
economy at a meeting initiated by the IMF in Tokyo on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The IMF and Japan will lead the way, pledging 4 billion dollars
each, while China's Hong Kong, Malaysia, Australia and Singapore
each will lend 1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia and South Korea also will contribute 500 million
respectively and another 3 billion dollars is expected to come
from the Asian Development Bank, the World Bank, China and others.
</P>
<P>
The loan package was the largest extended by the international
community to a single country since the Mexico peso crisis in
1994.
</P>
<P>
Thai newspapers said that Thai Finance Minister Thanong Bidaya,
who attended the meeting, was pleased with the package and the
funds will be used to bolster Thailand's depleted foreign exchange
reserves and calm investors nervous about Thailand's ability to
repay its debts.
</P>
<P>
The amount of the loan package is expected to expand to more
than 20 billion U.S. dollars as Thanong is negotiating further
loans with commercial banks, including some of Japan's largest
ones.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has pledged to take necessary measures to meet the
IMF's requirements, including raising value-added tax, reducing
the size of its financial industry, and tightening the
government's expenditures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Troops Foil Rebel Plan to Recruit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan troops mounted a
special operation in Trincomalee to foil rebel attempts to recruit
youth from among displaced people in the north, who were awaiting
return to Jaffna Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Tamil civilians have been stranded in Trincomalee
town since passenger services to Jaffna Peninsula came to a
standstill following the destruction of a passenger ferry off the
Manner coast early last month, said defense sources here today.
</P>
<P>
The sources also said they were compelled to take a series of
tough measures following intelligence reports of heavy rebel
activities aimed at recruiting youth from among displaced
families.
</P>
<P>
Jaffna Peninsula was once the stronghold of the Tamil rebels,
who have been fighting a 14-year war for a separate state in the
north and east of the country. Government troops recaptured the
peninsula in May last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
