<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China Environmental Protection Restrictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region, northwest Chin, has formulated its first lake protection
regulation in a move to stop the Bosten (Bagrax) Lake from
becoming further polluted.
</P>
<P>
Local environmental protection offices will join the fight
against pollution of Bosten lake, China's largest freshwater lake
and areas around it in keeping with the regulation.
</P>
<P>
The lake, located in the southeast part of the Yanqi Basin in
northern Xinjiang, has a drainage area of some 1,440 square
kilometers and is one of the leading water sources of the fairly
arid region.
</P>
<P>
But with local economic development in recent years, the area
around the Bosten lake suffered from environmental degradation of
varying extent.
</P>
<P>
And without adequate standard penalties, the local government
could not stop the environmental pollution, officials from the
autonomous regional environment protection office explained.
</P>
<P>
The regulation gives specifics of environmental controls and
protection around the lake and penalties for various violations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
