<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Seeks to Eradicate Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
pledged to eradicate poverty in the country, which still sees 11
percent of its 200-million population in poverty.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting on "the Integrated Guidance Program For Family
Welfare" held in Semarang, Central Java Monday, State Minister For
Population Haryono Suyono said that the government's poverty
alleviation program has reduced the number of people living in
poverty from 60 percent of the population in the 1970s to
approximately 11 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, Haryono said that development has only succeeded in
reducing poverty in urban areas but not in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
In the past three years, the number of rural people living in
poverty decreased only from 15.1 percent of the population to
14.38 percent or an average 1.5 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
The number of urban impoverished people decreased by some 16
percent or about 5 percent annually, he added.
</P>
<P>
To alleviate poverty, the Indonesian government has launched
the "Strengthening the Poverty Fight Program" focusing on
empowerment of the family, promotion of small and medium
businesses as well as cooperatives and development of eastern
Indonesia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
