<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Banking System Remains Stable in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's financial situation
remained stable in July with nearly 90 percent of cash emission
collected by the banking system, said Viktor Yushchenko, chairman
of the National Bank of Ukraine (NBU) here Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the banking system had allotted 4.22 billion
hryvnas (about 2.32 billion U.S. dollars) for wage payment and
social bonuses, which has become the largest allocation during
1997 and the second largest since September 1996.
</P>
<P>
In the same month, 3.75 billion hryvnas (about 2.06 billion
dollars) returned to the banking system. The high rate of cash
withdrawal from circulation showed the stability of the hryvnas'
exchange rate, prices and banking system as a whole, Yushchenko
said.
</P>
<P>
The average discount rate for state securities has increased
from 25.9 percent to 28 percent, which can be explained by
considerable conversion of long-term securities with one or one
and a half year term of redemption, noted the chairman.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the NBU is the only global currency buyer on
the Ukrainian stock market and has never initiated banking
support, which testifies to an increasing demand for hryvna. This
has made the NBU decide to reduce the NBU discount rate from 18
percent to 16 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
