<HEADLINE> Chinese Swimmers Dominate in World Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese swimmers showed
their prowess in the fin swimming competitions in the World Games
by taking five golds four silvers and two bronzes in Lahti on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Li Shaozhen from Guangdong province struck the gold medal three
times by winning the women's 100-meter and 50-meter events as well
as a team member in the 4x200m relay winning squad.
</P>
<P>
She clocked 39.37 seconds in the 100 meters, beating Russian
Julia Tshirikova to second in 43.29 and Czech Helena Kocourkova
third in 43.91.
</P>
<P>
Li also swam the fastest in the 50 meters final by touching
home in 19.58, with Svetlana Ganzha of Russia and Chinese Wu
Xiaohui finished second and third respectively.
</P>
<P>
Wu Xiaohui, also from Guangdong province, chopped up her title
from the 200-meter finals with a winning time 1:38.38.
</P>
<P>
Her teammate Wang Yan of Hubei province, clocked 1:39.75 for
the silver while Russian Natalia Mouzytshenko finished third.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese quartet, composed of Li Shaozhen, Wu Xiaohui, Wang
Yan and Zhu Xia, took the team title in the women's 4x200m relay
in 6:45.06, beating Russia and Hungary to second and third.
</P>
<P>
In the men's events, Russia halved the four gold medals at
stake, with the other two split by China and Hungary.
</P>
<P>
Liu Qiurong of Guangdong province, clocked the fastest time of
15.58 seconds in the 50-meter final, and Li Yong dashed ahead for
a 1-2 finish for China, beating Russian Alexander Netchitallo to
third.
</P>
<P>
However, Netchitallo revenged by taking the 100m title in 38.60
and awarded Russia a 1-2 finish with teammate Sergei Akapov,
beating Chinese Li Yong to third.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the Russian men's quartet outpaced their Chinese
peers to take the 4x100m relay in 2:34.66, beating China to second
and Italy third.
</P>
<P>
The men's 400m title went to Hungarian Norbert Savanya who
clocked 3:13.35, Chinese Hu Hailong finished second, ahead of
Russian Sergei Dokoutshaev. 
</P>
</TEXT>
