SINGAPORE -- The foreign ministers of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) ended their special meeting on
Cambodia here Monday with an agreement to remain engaged in their
efforts for restoring stability in Cambodia. In a joint statement
after the meeting, which lasted about four hours, the foreign
ministers said that as a result of the briefing, and the
discussions that followed, they "agreed that ASEAN will remain
engaged in its efforts to help restore political stability in
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Top leaders of the anti-Taliban alliance Monday
held a secret meeting to hammer out a strategy to oust the Islamic
militia from the Afghan capital Kabul. The meeting, which was
attended by all three strongmen in the anti-Taliban ranks, was
aimed at finalizing a strategy to seize Kabul and form a viable
political structure for the future Afghan government, said sources
in Peshawar, a major city in northwestern Pakistan.
</P>
