<BODY>
<HEADLINE> College Education Provided for Disabled People in Guangdong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 12 (Xinhua) -- This summer when Su Dan, a
girl with a disability, graduated from university, she was
approached by more than 30 companies.
</P>
<P>
This was in sharp contrast to just four years ago when she
graduated from middle school with high scores but was rejected by
quite a few universities.
</P>
<P>
Then Ji'nan University in Guangzhou, the capital of China's
Guangdong Province, learned of her plight and enrolled her in its
computer department.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Guangdong has made great efforts to help
people with disabilities enjoy their right to an education. After
1994, some 882 students who passed the entrance examinations went
on to further study at universities or technical schools, thanks
to the efforts of the Provincial Disabled Persons' Federation and
various departments.
</P>
<P>
The province has also built nearly 50 schools for disabled
people, enrolling more than 46,000 students, with children with
disabilities accounting for 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
It has opened dozens of job training classes to help the
disabled gain work skills. In 1988, the province set up China's
first job training center for the disabled, training some 300
blind people in massage. The Guangdong Institute for National
Minorities has opened a writers' class and offers a number of
special courses for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, various employment service centers for
the disabled have been opened in 21 cities and 100 counties in the
province, the employment rate of the disabled in the province has
increased from 55 percent in 1995 to 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
Su Dan has now gone on to a job in the Guangzhou Railway
Corporation, and believes that she can make a contribution to
society. "I couldn't finish my studies without the help of my
teachers and classmates. It's their love that gave me courage to
overcome my difficulties," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Aid-the-Poor Programs in Full Swing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- China's biggest city of Shanghai
has made progress in implementing a five-year plan to help the
poor in southwest China's Yunnan Province, according to a report
in today's "China Daily."
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai municipal committee of the Communist Party of
China and municipal government established an aid-the-poor leading
group and worked out the plan last September.
</P>
<P>
Funding and material support came from the city's 12 sectors,
such as industry, agriculture, education, science and technology,
culture, health and tourism.
</P>
<P>
The plan included 107 help-the-poor programs, with 732 million
yuan (87 million US dollars) in funding.
</P>
<P>
So far, the plan has aided construction of 105 primary schools
in Yunnan and helped about 12,500 drop-outs return to school.
</P>
<P>
Contributions to the assistance fund in Shanghai have reached
48.45 million yuan (5.8 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The city's Songjiang County and Yangpu District constructed
sugar cane factories to take advantage of the abundant output of
sugar cane in Yunnan's Simao and Maguan counties.
</P>
<P>
Since Shanghai became the market for the sugar, the province's
sugar and food industries have developed greatly.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Education Commission has signed 260 agreements
with its counterparts in the province to train some 2,000 local
teachers and set up two training bases.
</P>
<P>
Health departments in Shanghai also have dispatched travelling
medical teams and raised 1.14 million yuan to improve medical
service in more than 20 poor counties and villages in the
province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
