<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Rules Guide Upgrade for Phone Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Newly revised technical
requirements for program-controlled switching systems will soon
go into effect, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based newspaper quotes Jiang Shaobing, an official
of the Ministry of Post and Telecommunications (MPT) as saying
that the new regulations will require program-controlled switching
systems to have high capacity and top-quality technology to serve
digital telecommunications networks.
</P>
<P>
China's telephone networks are extending from the East into
Western regions and from urban to rural areas at an annual rate of
over 20 million land lines and six million mobile telephone
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000 when China achieves the goal of ensuring each
village has access to telephones, there will be more than 174
million land lines and over 30 million mobile telephone
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
To support the development of domestic enterprises and joint
ventures, the MPT has decided no more program-controlled switching
systems will be imported.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that great potential remains to be tapped in China's
program-controlled switching system market.
</P>
<P>
Switching systems with a capacity of 600 million lines need to
be installed if only 30 percent of the Chinese households get
telephones. Currently the country's switching systems can only
cope with about 100 million lines, the paper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
