<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Works Out Guideline Document on Natural Disasters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- China has worked out a guideline
document that suggests the country set up a national disaster
information center and adopt other disaster-alleviation measures,
today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The document, approved by experts from eight central government
ministries and departments, will be an important reference for
policy makers, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
China is one of several countries in the world afflicted by
some of the most serious natural disasters. In the past 48 years,
major disasters killed 10,000 and 20,000 people annually and cost
between one-sixth and one-fourth of China's revenues, according to
the paper.
</P>
<P>
The new document will help China establish networks to guide
disaster prevention within urban areas and enterprises while
working out relevant laws and regulations and injecting money into
disaster-alleviation projects, the paper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
