<HEADLINE> Anti-Taliban Alliance Hammers Out Plan to Storm Kabul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Top leaders of the
anti-Taliban alliance yesterday held a secret meeting to hammer
out a strategy to oust the Islamic militia from the Afghan capital
Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which was attended by all three strongman in the
anti- Taliban ranks, was aimed at finalizing a strategy to seize
Kabul and form a viable political structure for the future Afghan
government, said sources in Peshawar, a major city in northwestern
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
However, details of the meeting were not available at the
moment, the sources said, adding the outcome should become clear
in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
The sources, who have access to the alliance leadership, said
Afghanistan's former military chief Ahmad Masood, Uzbek warlord
Abdul Malik, Shiite Hezb-e-Hadat leader Karim Khalili and ousted
Afghan president Burhanuddin Rabbani were all present at the
meeting held in Masood-held Salang area, about 100 km north of
Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The top-level meeting itself could be seen as a positive sign
of a broad agreement within the alliance, the sources noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
