<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ to Cope with Youth Suicide Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand is working on a
national youth suicide strategy to deal with the high number of
youth suicides.
</P>
<P>
A local press report said today that Youth Affairs Minister
Deborah Morris will issue the framework for the strategy on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Youth suicide rates in New Zealand are reported to be among the
highest in the world: 44 males for every 100,000 students, second
only to Finland and 13 females for every 100,000, the highest in
the world.
</P>
<P>
National statistics for 1995 showed that 156 people killed
themselves, and 1,310 were admitted to hospital after suicide
attempts.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey of 2,000 young people in schools found that 18
percent have had some thoughts of suicide and 7 percent have
attempted it.
</P>
<P>
The strategy will stress the need of encouraging young people
to seek help when they face an emotional crisis, and a general
improvement of attitudes and understanding of emotional problems
and suicidal behavior.
</P>
<P>
It will recommend extra funding for mental health, recruiting
more mental health workers and reducing charges.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mercosur Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are some
economic news briefs in Mercosur countries.

Mercosur Countries Economic Test
</P>
<P>
Montevideo -- The Mercosur's Council of Foreign Trade organized
a meeting on August 7 and 8 in Paraguay to examine economic
performance of the trading bloc partners.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur relationships with Mexico and the European Union
were studied in the meeting, along with the system of inspection
of regional shipments.

Argentina-Chile Defense Cooperation
</P>
<P>
Buenos Aires-- Argentina and Chile exchanged ideas about
defense and security issues and made up proposals regarding common
measures on such topics at a meeting held on August 4 to 5.
</P>
<P>
Both sides ratified bilateral military maneuvers to take place
in early 1998 and stressed their active and coordinated
participation in the "Ottawa Process" to get rid of
antipersonal mines.
</P>
<P>
In the meeting, both countries coordinated their positions on
international security, disarmament and United Nations issues.

Argentina Accounted for Trade Deficit
</P>
<P>
Buenos Aires -- Argentina had a trade deficit of 1.27 million
dollars in first half of 1997, according to the National
Institute of Surveys and Statistics (indec) figures.
</P>
<P>
The shortage was a result of 12.56 billion dollars total exports
along with imports for 13.83 billion.

Brazil Forecasts 8.28 Billion Dollars Capital Inflows
</P>
<P>
Rio de Janeiro -- Brazil forecasted 8.28 billion dollars in
foreign capitals over this year, said the National Association of
Investment Banks.
</P>
<P>
The goverment expects to add 20 billion dollars to this year
inflows, showing foreign investors trust in Brazil.

7 Percent Growth Expected in Argentina
</P>
<P>
Buenos Aires -- Argentinan economy could grow 7 percent this
year, figures assessed through evolution of loans and deposits,
altogether with other guides, said Finance Minister Roque
Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
The minister also stressed rises in private loans, foreign
trade and investments increases, as suitable conditions for
economy.

CIM Describes Brazil Barriers as Necessary Evil
</P>
<P>
Montevideo -- Representatives of Mercosur Industry Council
(CIM) considered brazilian restrictive meassures to foreign
products as a necessary evil, and they too considered those
meassures are against Mercosur spirit.
</P>
<P>
Brazil started barriers in its imports since April this year.

Argentina-Uruguay Congress on Animal Production
</P>
<P>
Montevideo -- Uruguay and Argentina will accomplished the
first binational congress on animal production on September
in the Uruguayan city of Paysandu.
</P>
<P>
The congress will count on lectures by both countries experts
and foreign guests. the main issue in the meeting will be
"breeding technology for Mercosur". (to be continued)


