<HEADLINE> Kohl Rejects Call for Cabinet Reshuffle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl has
rejected a call to reshuffle his cabinet as "unnecessary", a
German government spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
Kohl was quoted as making the remark during his vacation in
Austria after Finance Minister Theo Waigel suggested over the
weekend that the German cabinet be reshuffled this year in order
to put the governing coalition in a better position for the next
general elections scheduled for Autumn next year.
</P>
<P>
Germany's governing coalition is consisted of Kohl's Christian
Democratic Union (CDU), Waigel's Christian Social Union (CSU) and
the junior partner Free Democratic Party (FDP).
</P>
<P>
Despite Kohl's opposition, CSU Vice-General-Secretary Joachim
Herrmann voiced support for Waigel's proposal.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German newspaper Berliner Morgenpost,
Herrmann noted that his party could be less represented in the
cabinet when the Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications,
currently held by the CSU, is dissolved under a government plan by
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Due to its successful policy, the CSU should not be punished by
the government reform, Herrmann said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
