<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's Thyssen, Krupp Eye Full Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Germany's two largest steel
companies Thyssen and Krupp would begin talks next month which
could lead to a full merger, German media reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Thyssen and Krupp, once arch-rivals, agreed in March to merge
their steel-making units after Krupp launched an unsolicited bid
to take over its larger rival Thyssen.
</P>
<P>
According to the German news magazine Der Spiegel, the two
companies would begin talks in September with a view to merge the
rest of their operations after their steel joint venture begins
operating at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
The merger was long overdue because the two companies were
still too small by international standard to compete with U.S. or
Japanese giants in areas such as trade in raw materials or car
components, Der Spiegel said.
</P>
<P>
A full merger would not only produce an entity which would be
the world's fifth largest steel maker, but also one of the most
important supplier of the automotive industry, the magazine said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
