<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Rejects Oklahoma Bombing Defendant's Retrial Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- A federal judge in Denver,
Colorado, rejected on Monday Timothy McVeigh's bid for a new trial
in the Oklahoma City bombing in 1995 and ordered McVeigh to appear
for formal sentencing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a motion for a new trial filed last month, McVeigh's
attorneys argued jurors were unfairly swayed by pretrial publicity
and devastating testimony from bombing survivors and victims'
relatives.
</P>
<P>
But U.S. District Judge Richard Matsch sided with prosecutors,
who contended McVeigh received a fair trial, according to news
reports.
</P>
<P>
In June, McVeigh was convicted of murder, conspiracy and
weapons-related counts and sentenced to die in the April 19, 1995,
bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma. The
bombing killed 168 people and injured more than 500. A jury
sentenced him to death by injection.
</P>
<P>
Matsch "ensured the McVeigh trial not only was fair, but indeed
was close to perfect," prosecutor Sean Connelly wrote in a brief
opposing McVeigh's motion for a new trial.
</P>
<P>
"McVeigh's conviction was the product of a fair trial in which
the evidence of guilt was so overwhelming that the jury could not
rationally have reached any other verdict," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
