<DOCNO> XIE19970812.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Government Orders to Test Guam Radar Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States government
is ordering the immediate testing of low-altitude warning systems
in the nation's airports following disclosure that the system was
not working on Guam when Korean Air Flight 801 crashed.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Aviation Administration announced today that, as a
precaution, it "is directing the testing of all of the Minimum
Safe Altitude Warning Systems within next two days."
</P>
<P>
There are about 200 of the systems at U.S. airports, designed
to issue an alert if a jet is flying too low. Controllers on the
ground then warn the pilot.
</P>
<P>
The National Transportation Safety Board reported Sunday that
an error was apparently inserted into the Guam system's software
and it was not working at the time of the Korean Air plane crash,
which killed 226 people.
</P>
<P>
Investigators say the faulty system was not to blame for the
crash. But they say a properly working system could have allowed
air traffic controllers to direct the pilot of the Boeing 747 to
pull the plane to a higher altitude when the plane approached Guam
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
The FAA is also using data taken from Flight 801 to simulate the
jet's route and figure out when the alert should have been given,
said George Black, an NTSB member. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
