<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton to Visit Africa Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The White House said on
Monday that President Bill Clinton is still considering making a
trip to Africa early next year, and what has not been decided is
his itinerary.
</P>
<P>
But whatsoever of his itinerary, South Africa is certain to be
included in his African travel, White House spokesman Mike McCurry
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's plan to visit Africa reflects his shifting much more
attention to international affairs in his second term, observers
here said.
</P>
<P>
In his first term, Clinton paid relatively little attention to
Africa and U.S. aid to that continent is only a fraction of its
14 billion U.S. dollar annual foreign aid budget.
</P>
<P>
Former Secretary of State Warren Christopher traveled to
Africa last year and made some proposals including forming a task
force by African countries to deal with peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
The United States has this year sent some Army troops to the
continent to do training of some countries' troops for that
mission.
</P>
<P>
First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton also made a six-nation tour
of Africa in March. And after her visit, the president joined
bipartisan congressional leaders in June to urge a series of trade
measures designed to encourage free-market reforms in Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
