<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Waigel Wants to Reduce Germany's Contributions to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
has called for a reduction in Germany's financial contributions to
the European Union (EU) because Germany has become less well-off
after its reunification in 1990, a German news magazine reported
today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German weekly Der Spiegel, Waigel
said: "It is not going to work in the long run that only one
country, Germany, shoulders 60 percent of the total EU spendings".
</P>
<P>
A new, more favorable burden-sharing system should be found for
the period after the year 2000, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Waigel, Germany currently contributes over 20
billion marks (11 billion U.S. dollars) a year to the EU, which is
0.6 percent of its gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Germany should pay about 0.4 percent of its GDP to the EU at
most, which is six to seven billion marks (3.2 to 3.8 billion
dollars) less than the current level, Waigel said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
