<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Rebounds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar rallied sharply
Monday from its big pre-weekend selloff, powered by resumed
appetite for dollars and doubts that Germany is preparing to raise
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar slid 2.9 percent against the yen and 1.1
percent against the mark on Friday, when U.S. stock and bond
prices plunged.
</P>
<P>
The dollar settled in New York at 116.12 yen, up from its
nearly one-month low of 114.95 yen Friday. The dollar cost 1.8634
marks, up from 1.8473. The pound cost 1.5828 U.S. dollars, down
from 1.5855 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average, which lost 156 points,
rallied from a 50-point deficit late Monday to close up 30.89 at
8,062.11. The 30-year Treasury bond also reversed from a deficit
close slightly higher.
</P>
<P>
Further helping the dollar was receding speculation that the
Bundesbank would raise the short-term interest rate known as the
repo rate on Tuesday. Traders said resilient weakness in Germany's
economy made higher rates unlikely.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday:
</P>
<P>
1.5275 Swiss francs, up from 1.5103; 6.2803 French francs, up
from 6.2238; 1,814.00 Italian lire, up from 1,802.50; 1.3934
Canadian dollars, up from 1.3896.  
</P>
</TEXT>
