<HEADLINE> US Machine Tools Demand Up 20 Percent in 1st Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Demand for machine tools in
the U.S. rose by nearly 20 percent in the first half of this year,
The Washington Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
Orders for machine tools in the first six month totaled 4.4
billion dollars, comparing with 3.7 billion dollars in the same
six months of 1996, according to a joint report Sunday by the
American Machine Tool Distributors Association and the Association
of Manufacturing Technology as high as 81.3 percent from the 493
million dollars in the same month of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Machine tools are used to shape metal in making products such
as cars and aircraft and demand for the tools is viewed as an
indictor of the pace of future manufacturing in the country.
</P>
