<HEADLINE> U.S. Admits Long Way to Go in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
admitted that there is still "a long way to go" in Bosnia despite
some progress has been made after a visit to the Balkans by a U.S.
special envoy.
</P>
<P>
"In Bosnia, no matter how much progress you make, you still
have a long way to go," State Department spokesman James Rubin
told a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
However, when asked to assess the trip by U.S. envoy Richard
Holbrooke last week to the Balkans, Rubin said that "significant
progress" has been made in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We have to look at Bosnia as a motion picture and not a
snapshot," Rubin said. "We see... that progress has been made,
significant progress."
</P>
<P>
During his trip to the Balkans, Holbrooke resolved a dispute
among Bosnia's leaders over diplomatic posts and gained promise
from the Bosnian Serbs that former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan
Karadzic will disappear from politics.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts have noted that the trip was a failure as
Bosnia's leaders still have differences over a series of issues on
how to unite the Serbs, Muslims and Croats into one nation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Holbrooke was believed to have compromised on
dealing with Karadzic by giving Serbs a period of grace. Karadzic
was indicted as a major war criminal by Washington and regarded as
a major obstacle in the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
