<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Travel Fund Squeezed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The White House is cutting
back travel by presidential aides as its travel budget began
creeping too close to its limit for the fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
After accounting for the travel cost of the trips U.S.
President Bill Clinton is expected to take between now and
September 30, when the fiscal year ends, the White House was left
with a "headroom cushion" of only 40,000 dollars, said White House
Press Secretary Mike McCurry Monday.
</P>
<P>
But McCurry said the White House wasn't worried the Clintons
would run out of travel funds before the end of the fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Deputy White House chief of staff John Podesta is now
personally approving each official traveler on Air Force One and
other trips.
</P>
<P>
But McCurry said Monday the measure is just a "prudent effort
to keep the size of the presidential entourage at a minimum."
</P>
<P>
"I'm sure this happens and has happened in the past," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The restrictions apply only to "White House aides, staff-type
folks" and exclude official military, medical or Secret Service
personnel, McCurry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
